  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"ahri","win":["Ahri","Ahri","Ahri","Ahri","Ahri","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Ahri's Charm (E) into full combo threatens a kill the instant she hits 3 items of range advantage on you; you have no answer until W (Parallel Convergence) is up to trade back or E to dash away."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Spirit Rush (R) gives Ahri three dashes to reset Charm angles and reposition mid-fight, while your own Chronobreak just heals and slows — she still outduels you in a straight 1v1 here."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Once you finish Zhonya's or Riftmaker and hit level 6-7 items, your stun-into-full-rotation burst finally out-trades her Charm poke, and she has to respect your all-in instead of freely farming with Orb of Deception."},{"when":"Late","text":"Late Ekko is a pick-and-teamfight machine — your R rewind punishes any Ahri dive attempt and your AoE stun turns fights, while she's stuck kiting on cooldowns."}],"wants":{"you":["Survive lane without overextending into Charm range","Farm safely with Q poke and hold W for her all-in","Reach 2-item spike before forcing side-lane fights"],"foe":["Land Charm from max range to chain a kill","Use Fox-Fire proc + Q to zone you off the wave","Roam off 2 mid-priority waves before you scale"]},"early":"Ahri's Orb of Deception poke chunks you for free from level 1-2, and once she hits level 3 the Charm-into-full-combo threat means you have to play the lane from max range, giving up CS or eating chip damage every time you push. Your Timewinder (Q) trades evenly at best, but you lack the burst to punish her positioning before level 6, so you're mostly surviving and looking for a W stun on her cooldowns.","mid":"Spirit Rush at 6 lets Ahri reposition through your stun and Charm setups, so her all-in window is genuinely scary even though your kit comes online too — she can flash-adjacent an escape or engage that you can't easily punish with just Chronobreak's heal-and-slow. You need to bait out her dashes with W (Parallel Convergence) placement and only commit when she's spent Charm or is out of Spirit Rush charges.","late":"By 2-item Ekko your burst combo (E-Q-R or full rotation) outpaces her all-in, and Zhonya's/defensive stats let you shrug off her engage before flipping it — from here you should look to roam and force fights where your AoE stun and rewind swing skirmishes, since her kit has no way to punish your positioning once she's used Charm.","whys":["Ahri's poke and range advantage let her win most level 1-2 trades before your combo comes online","Landing Charm at level 3 sets up a kill threat you can't reliably answer yet","Her damage and mobility edge still outclasses your trade potential through level 5","Spirit Rush at 6 gives her more repositioning tools than your ult provides, keeping the all-in in her favor","Same logic carries into levels 4-5/6 window — her kit peaks faster and cleaner than yours","Your first completed item finally gives your combo enough burst to flip 1st-item trades in your favor","With items and levels stacked, your rewind-enabled all-in and teamfight stun outscale her kiting kit"]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"akali","win":["Ekko","Skill","Skill","Ekko","Akali","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Your Timewinder poke plus a well-placed W stun punishes Akali before she has Shroud (W) up on a short cooldown, letting you win most early trades if you swing first."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Akali's Perfect Execution (R) reset combo threatens a full kill through Shroud stealth, and if you're caught out of position after she Twilight Shrouds in, you can die before you even see her again."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Once you've got Zhonya's or a defensive component, you can survive her all-in and use your own R to punish her over-commit — the trade swings back toward you as your combo damage and survivability both improve."},{"when":"Late","text":"Late-game your AoE stun and pick potential in teamfights outweigh her single-target assassination, especially since Shroud does nothing to stop your zone control."}],"wants":{"you":["Poke her down before she has W (Twilight Shroud) available","Hold cooldowns to punish any Shroud-engage with your own combo","Group for teamfights where AoE stun beats her single-target dive"],"foe":["Land Shroud engages when your key cooldowns are down","Use R resets to snowball a solo kill at level 6","Roam under Shroud stealth to bypass vision"]},"early":"You have the early trading advantage here — your Q harass plus W stun punishes Akali's shorter-range poke before she has energy or Shroud cooldown to play around, so you should look to shove and threaten all-ins levels 3-5. She has to play passively until she has enough energy to threaten Five Point Strike combos, giving you a real window to push your advantage.","mid":"Level 6 flips the script hard: Akali's ultimate gives her a reset-heavy execute combo that can delete you through her own stealth cloud, and if she catches you without Zhonya's or a flash up, you simply die. This is her best window in the whole matchup, so you need to play safer around her level 6 spike, ward her flanks, and avoid overextending even if you were ahead in the earlier levels.","late":"Once you've got your first defensive item you're back in control — your combo burst outtrades her all-in, and by full build your ability to stun a whole team and threaten picks with R makes you the better teamfighter, since Shroud is a single-target escape/engage tool that does nothing against your zone denial.","whys":["Your poke and stun punish her before she has Shroud up, giving you the early trade lead","Skill expression at this stage is close — whoever lands the first big cooldown usually wins the trade","Same even footing continues as both kits are on comparable cooldown timers here","Your all-in potential and item lead let you keep pressing the advantage from levels 4-5","Her level 6 reset combo through Shroud stealth is a genuine kill threat you can't fully play around yet","Your first item's survivability and burst let you flip the trade back in your favor","Your AoE stun and pick potential outclass her single-target dive in the late-game teamfight context"]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"akshan","win":["Skill","Akshan","Akshan","Akshan","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Akshan's Avengerang (Q) poke plus Going Rogue camouflage lets him harass and reposition for free, and his passive shield off minion kills makes him tough to punish once he's ahead in the trade."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Comeuppance (R) is a long-range execute that can end your life from off-screen if you're caught low, and its global range means you're never fully safe even when you think you've escaped."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Once you hit your first item and have your full combo plus Zhonya's, you can force fights where Akshan's short burst window and reliance on autos/Q poke can't keep up with your stun-into-rewind damage."},{"when":"Late","text":"Late-game your AoE stun and teamfight presence outweigh his pick-oriented kit, though you still need to respect Comeuppance if any ally is low."}],"wants":{"you":["Play safe under turret through levels 3-5 poke","Avoid dying to set up his revive-and-execute chain","Look for your all-in once you hit level 6-7 with items"],"foe":["Poke with Q and dodge trades using camouflage","Farm safely and shield off minions to sustain","Look for Comeuppance snipes on low-health targets"]},"early":"Akshan's Avengerang poke chips you down at low cost, and his passive lets him heal off minion last-hits so he doesn't even need to hit you to stay healthy in the trade — this makes early lane frustrating since you're the one taking consistent chip damage while he can disengage into camouflage after pushing. You mostly want to hold priority for jungle pathing and avoid greedy trades into his poke.","mid":"His level 6 Comeuppance is a genuine threat to anyone on your team sitting below its execute threshold, global range and all, so you need to respect kill potential even off-screen and play around vision to avoid feeding him easy picks. Your own Chronobreak doesn't match his utility for punishing overextension, so this window still favors him.","late":"Once you've got your first item and level up your combo, you can finally force fights on your terms — your stun locks him down before he can kite with autos, and Zhonya's or defensive stats neutralize his poke-based damage. From here you should look to group and use your AoE stun to win skirmishes, while staying aware that a single low ally still dies to a well-timed Comeuppance.","whys":["Both champions are still figuring out damage windows at level 1-2, making this an even skill matchup","His poke and sustain from Avengerang plus passive shield win the early trades in his favor","Camouflage repositioning and continued poke keep the advantage on his side through this window","Comeuppance execute threat and overall kit tempo still favor him heading into level 6","Your item and level spike finally let your combo outpace his poke-reliant damage","Your all-in potential with a completed item flips the trade decisively in your favor","Your AoE stun and teamfight presence outclass his single-target pick kit in the late game"]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"anivia","win":["Ekko","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko","Anivia"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Anivia is fragile and immobile before she has a Crystallize (W) wall to punish your engage, so your Q-W-E combo can bully her off the wave and force her to play from max range."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Even with Glacial Storm (R) online, Anivia still lacks the mobility to escape your engage — your W stun catches her before she can wall you off, so this window stays yours."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Your burst combo with a completed item deletes her squishy HP pool through Flash Frost pressure, and she has no way to disengage a committed Ekko all-in."},{"when":"Late","text":"Late-game Anivia's wave-clear and zone control from Glacial Storm plus her Rebirth passive give her real teamfight staying power, letting her out-scale your pick potential if the game goes long enough."}],"wants":{"you":["Punish her immobility with early aggressive trades","Bait Flash Frost before committing to your all-in","Snowball your lead before she scales into late-game zone control"],"foe":["Land Flash Frost stuns to set up burst combos","Use Crystallize walls to cut off your engage angles","Survive to late-game where Glacial Storm zoning takes over"]},"early":"Anivia is one of the squishiest, least mobile mid laners in the game before level 6, and your dash-heavy kit lets you dictate every trade — bully her under turret with Q harass and look for all-in windows whenever her Flash Frost (Q) is down, since she has zero escape otherwise. This is one of your strongest early matchups if you play aggressively.","mid":"Glacial Storm gives her a strong wave-clear and zoning tool, but it doesn't solve her lack of mobility — you can still engage through or around her Crystallize wall with your dash on E, and her damage output still can't match your burst combo in a direct fight. Keep pressuring her whenever Flash Frost is down and look to end the lane before she gets to scale.","late":"This is the one phase where the tables turn: Anivia's Rebirth passive gives her a free second life in fights, and her Glacial Storm zone control plus wave-clear lets her scale into a real teamfight threat if the game runs long. You want to close the game out before she reaches this point, since her late-game utility can offset your earlier lane dominance.","whys":["Anivia's fragility and lack of mobility let you dominate level 1-2 trades outright","Continued lack of an escape tool keeps this window firmly in your favor as you punish her positioning","Your engage tools still outclass her limited kit before she reaches level 6","Same trend continues into levels 4-5 as your combo damage outpaces her squishy HP pool","Even with her ultimate online, she still lacks the mobility to escape your stun-into-combo engage","Your completed item burst deletes her before Glacial Storm zoning can offset the damage","Her Rebirth passive and Glacial Storm zone control finally give her the tools to outscale you late"]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"annie","win":["Skill","Skill","Annie","Annie","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Once Annie's passive Pyromania is charged, her Q-stun into full combo threatens a kill you can't trade back into — you have to play around her stun charge, tracking how many spells she's cast."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Summon: Tibbers (R) adds a huge burst of extra damage plus a persistent zoning threat, making her all-in even scarier and harder to walk away from unpunished."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Once you complete your first item, your own combo burst and mobility let you dodge her stun-reliant engage and punish her lack of escape outside of Flash."},{"when":"Late","text":"Late-game your mobility and pick potential outclass her immobile burst-mage kit, since she has no way to escape or reposition once she's used her stun."}],"wants":{"you":["Track her Pyromania stun charge to avoid free kills","Farm safely and wait for your own item/level spikes","Punish her lack of mobility once you have a lead"],"foe":["Charge Pyromania and land the stun for a full combo","Use Tibbers to zone the wave and threaten all-ins","Force fights before you scale into your mobility advantage"]},"early":"Annie's Disintegrate poke is annoying but manageable, but the real danger is her stunned Pyromania proc — track her spell casts closely because a charged stun into full combo can delete you from near-full health, especially once she hits level 3-5 and has the combo damage to back it up. Play safer around her charged passive and look to punish her when it's on cooldown.","mid":"Tibbers at level 6 adds a wall of extra damage and area denial on top of an already-scary stun combo, so her all-in window here is one of the most dangerous burst combos in the mid lane — you have to respect this completely and avoid giving her easy stun setups. This remains her strongest phase of the matchup.","late":"Once you've got your first item, your mobility and dash-based kit let you dodge her stun and punish her immobility — she has no escape besides Flash, so a whiffed Q or Tibbers on cooldown means she's dead to your engage. From here your pick potential and repositioning advantage only grow, making you the far scarier threat in skirmishes and teamfights.","whys":["Both champions are still working with limited tools at level 1-2, keeping this window even","Same even footing continues as neither combo is fully online yet","Annie's charged Pyromania stun into full combo threatens a kill you can't answer at this level","Tibbers unlocking and her all-in combo damage keep this window in her favor through levels 4-5","Your first-item combo and mobility finally let you dodge her stun and punish her lack of escape","Your continued mobility and damage advantage extend your lead through the late-mid transition","Your mobility and pick potential outclass her immobile burst kit once she's spent her stun"]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"aurelionsol","win":["Ekko","Skill","Skill","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Aurelion Sol is clunky and immobile at level 1-2, but by level 3-5 his stacked Singularity (Q) black hole and Starsurge stun start punishing your approach if you walk into his zone carelessly."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Voice of Light (R) gives him a long-range poke-and-slow that pairs with his black hole zone, but he still lacks a hard escape, so your engage windows stay strong even after 6."},{"when":"1st item","text":"With a completed item your combo burst punishes his lack of mobility hard — he has no way to disengage a committed Ekko dive once Starsurge is down."},{"when":"Late","text":"Late-game his black hole zone control and poke range give him strong teamfight presence, but you can still flank through his zone with your dash and punish his positioning if he overextends."}],"wants":{"you":["Punish his lack of mobility early with aggressive trades","Dodge Starsurge before committing to your all-in","Snowball your early lead into a fast mid-game power spike"],"foe":["Stack Singularity to control zone and farm safely","Land Starsurge to set up burst combos","Poke from range with Voice of Light once you're near"]},"early":"Aurelion Sol is slow to ramp and has zero mobility at level 1-2, so you can bully him hard with your dash-based engage before his Singularity stacks get big enough to zone you out — look for all-in windows whenever Starsurge (Q) is down since he has no escape otherwise. By level 3-5 his growing black hole makes him harder to just walk into, so time your engages around his stun cooldown.","mid":"Voice of Light adds real poke range at level 6, but it doesn't give him any way to disengage — he's still rooted in place if you commit past his zone, so your all-in potential remains strong through this window as long as you dodge or bait his Starsurge stun first. This stays one of your more comfortable matchups into the mid-game.","late":"His black hole zone control and long-range poke make him a real threat in structured teamfights, and you need to respect his ability to poke you down before you can close the gap — but his complete lack of a mobility or escape tool means a flank through his zone still punishes him hard whenever he's caught out of position.","whys":["His lack of mobility and slow early ramp let you dominate level 1-2 trades outright","His growing black hole zone starts to punish careless engages, though you can still play around Starsurge cooldowns","Same even footing continues as his zone control grows but still can't fully answer your engage timing","Your dash-based engage and combo damage keep the advantage in your favor through levels 4-5","His added poke from Voice of Light doesn't solve his lack of escape, so your all-in window remains strong at level 6","Your completed item burst punishes his immobility hard, extending your lead into the item phase","Your flanking mobility continues to punish his positioning even as his zone control matters more late"]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"aurora","win":["Skill","Skill","Aurora","Aurora","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Aurora's Between Worlds (E) dash into stun combo starts hitting hard once she has levels in it, and her sustained damage from Vile Flowers stacking punishes extended trades you can't easily escape."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"The Weirding (R) gives her a long, disruptive slow-and-damage zone that pairs with her dash to make her all-in genuinely dangerous, and she can chase you down even after you use your E to disengage."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Once you complete your first item, your burst combo and stun finally let you punish her aggression — her kit has no hard escape once you land your engage first."},{"when":"Late","text":"Late-game your teamfight AoE stun and pick potential outweigh her single-target dueling kit, though she remains dangerous in extended skirmishes if she catches you isolated."}],"wants":{"you":["Survive her stacking poke without overextending","Hold cooldowns to punish her dash-in once it's used","Reach your item spike before forcing fights"],"foe":["Stack Vile Flowers with poke to build toward a burst combo","Use Between Worlds to dash in and stun for a full combo","Chase with The Weirding to close out a kill"]},"early":"Aurora's stacking poke from Vile Flowers and her dash-stun combo via Between Worlds make early trades risky once she's leveled her kit up, and by levels 3-5 she can punish any extended trade with a full combo you can't easily disengage from. You want to play patiently, avoid stacking her passive on yourself, and wait for a cooldown window to strike back.","mid":"Her ultimate The Weirding adds a persistent slow-and-damage zone that makes chasing you down after your E dash much easier, so her all-in at level 6 is genuinely threatening — she can punish overextension hard and there's little you can do defensively besides playing around her engage cooldown. This remains her best window in the matchup.","late":"Once you've got your first item, your combo burst and stun let you flip trades back in your favor — if you engage first before she can stack her passive, she has no way to escape your all-in. From there your AoE teamfight stun and pick potential outclass her more single-target dueling kit, though she's still dangerous if she isolates you in a skirmish.","whys":["Both kits are still ramping at level 1-2, making this an even, skill-driven window","Same even footing continues as neither combo fully outclasses the other yet","Her stacking poke and dash-stun combo start punishing your trades once her kit is leveled","Continued pressure from her Between Worlds engage and Vile Flowers stacking keep this window in her favor","Her ultimate's chase potential and disruption keep the all-in advantage on her side at level 6","Your first-item combo burst and stun let you flip trades and punish her aggression from here on","Your AoE teamfight stun and pick potential outclass her more single-target kit in the late game"]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"azir","win":["Ekko","Ekko","Skill","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko","Azir"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Once you have Q-W-E online you can punish Azir's low base kit before he gets soldiers rolling for free poke, especially if he whiffs Conquering Sands trying to zone you off minions."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Chronobreak lets you shrug off Emperor's Divide all-ins and reset the fight — Azir has no hard peel for a rewound Ekko diving through his soldier wall."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Azir spikes brutally hard once his mythic-tier item comes online, turning every wave clear into heavy poke damage you can't out-trade."},{"when":"Late","text":"Late Azir with Rabadon's and full soldier uptime out-scales your burst combo in teamfights — you win 1v1 windows but lose the raw scaling war."}],"wants":{"you":["Force fights before Azir hits his soldier-spam power spike","Punish his short dash range at level 3-5 with all-in windows","Use Parallel Convergence to threaten roams under his tower"],"foe":["Turret-plant soldiers and poke you off minions safely","Wait for his item spike to out-range your trades","Save Emperor's Divide to displace you away from allies in 5v5s"]},"early":"You're the aggressor from level 3 onward — Azir's soldiers have a slow summon animation and short dash range early, so if you catch him without a soldier up near you, your Q-AA-W combo punishes him hard before his kit comes online.","mid":"Level 6 is your best all-in window: Chronobreak means a bad engage from you isn't a real risk, and Azir has no way to burst you down before your rewind saves you, so you can force fights he'd rather avoid.","late":"Once Azir has his mythic-tier item and full soldier rotations, he starts winning wave clear, poke, and teamfight range simultaneously — his ultimate repositions your whole team while soldiers deal free chip damage, so late you need picks and vision rather than straight fights.","whys":["You out-trade Azir's weak early base kit before soldiers ramp up, punishing his short E dash range.","Your all-in combo is fully online by level 3-5 while Azir still lacks reliable poke uptime, keeping this phase yours.","Both sides are figuring out wave management and soldier placement here — neither has a clean edge yet.","Chronobreak-adjacent aggression (pre-6 all-ins backed by good trades) keeps you ahead as levels 4-5 hit.","Your level 6 all-in window with Chronobreak lets you dive through soldiers with a safety net Azir can't answer.","Post-6 you can force fights on your terms since a rewound engage carries almost no risk for you.","Azir's item spike and soldier scaling eventually out-damage and out-range your kit, flipping the late game to him."]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"brand","win":["Ekko","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Brand's Sear-Pillar combo threatens hard but his mana costs are brutal early, so once you have Q-W online you can punish his all-in attempts and win short trades."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Your Chronobreak completely trumps Pyroclasm — you can dodge his ultimate's bounce entirely with a well-timed rewind, denying him his main kill tool."},{"when":"1st item","text":"You out-scale him hard once Everfrost or your burst item lands — Brand's damage is real but immobile, and you can dive him before he lands his full combo."},{"when":"Late","text":"Brand becomes a pure poke-and-teamfight AoE threat late, but he still has zero mobility, so your dive potential with Chronobreak keeps you the dominant threat in skirmishes."}],"wants":{"you":["Dodge Sear skillshots and punish his low mobility with all-ins","Save Chronobreak to bait and avoid Pyroclasm bounces","Snowball wave control since Brand has no real answer to your dives"],"foe":["Land Sear to set up his full stun-into-burst combo","Poke you down with Conflagration before you close the gap","Hope his passive Blaze procs enough to zone you off farm"]},"early":"You're ahead from level 1 — Brand is entirely reliant on landing a skillshot stun to do anything, and if he misses Sear you can freely all-in him with your Q-W combo since he has no mobility to escape or punish you back.","mid":"This lead only grows at level 6: Chronobreak lets you dodge Pyroclasm's bounce or reset after eating it, so Brand's ultimate — his best teamfight tool — barely threatens you, and you keep diving him every time he's caught out of position.","late":"Immobility is a death sentence against a scaled Ekko, so even as Brand's poke damage becomes genuinely scary in teamfights, you can still flank and burst him down with Chronobreak before his team can peel, making this matchup lopsided start to finish.","whys":["Brand's all-in relies entirely on landing Sear, and you already punish misses hard with your early trade pattern.","Your Q-W combo out-trades his poke attempts while his mana costs limit how often he can throw skillshots.","You continue snowballing the lane as your combo comes fully online and Brand still lacks any escape tool.","Level 4-5 sees you comfortably ahead on tempo, using superior mobility to punish any overextension.","Chronobreak completely neutralizes Pyroclasm, turning Brand's signature ultimate into a non-threat for you.","Your item spike lets you dive through his poke and burst him down before he lands his full stun combo.","Even scaled, Brand's total lack of mobility means your dive threat with Chronobreak keeps you ahead late."]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"cassiopeia","win":["Cassiopeia","Cassiopeia","Cassiopeia","Cassiopeia","Cassiopeia","Cassiopeia","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Cassiopeia's Noxious Blast-Twin Fang combo poisons you from a safe distance and her passive movement speed on non-champions makes her impossible to kite in melee range."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Petrifying Gaze is a massive threat to your dive plan — if she lands even a partial-facing stun on you, she chunks your HP bar before you can even start your combo."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Rabadon's or Liandry's timing makes her poke genuinely unbearable — her DPS in extended trades scales far above what your burst window can offset."},{"when":"Late","text":"Only once you're fully itemized with Chronobreak up does your all-in finally threaten her — you can dodge a stun with a rewind and burst her squishy backline before she reacts."}],"wants":{"you":["Farm safely under tower and avoid extended trades vs her poison DPS","Bait out Petrifying Gaze before committing to any all-in","Wait until full build to use Chronobreak for a dive window"],"foe":["Poke you relentlessly with Noxious Blast and stacked Twin Fang","Ground you with Miasma zones to control neutral objectives","Land Petrifying Gaze to guarantee a kill combo"]},"early":"Cassiopeia simply out-ranges and out-damages you in every early trade — her poison stacks punish you for staying in minion range, and her serpentine movement bonus means you can't even catch her with Q to start a fight on your terms.","mid":"Her power only compounds through level 6: Petrifying Gaze threatens a full stun-into-burst combo that can delete you before Chronobreak is even relevant, so you're forced to play around her cooldowns rather than initiate.","late":"Only with a completed burst item and Chronobreak ready do you finally have the tools to flank her backline and punish a bad stun attempt, since by then your one-shot combo can outpace her poison DPS if you catch her isolated.","whys":["Cassiopeia's early poke damage and kiting via her passive speed bonus let her win every extended trade against you.","She continues to dominate lane exchanges as her stacked poison from Twin Fang punishes any prolonged proximity.","Her ability to zone you off farm with Noxious Blast keeps compounding her lead through this phase.","By level 4-5 her damage output and range advantage still outclass your trade pattern in lane.","Petrifying Gaze at level 6 is a genuine kill threat that outweighs your own ultimate's value in this window.","Her poke plus stun combo remains the bigger threat even as your kit comes online, keeping her favoured.","Once you're fully itemized, Chronobreak finally gives you the dive tool to punish her lack of escape and burst her down."]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"diana","win":["Skill","Diana","Skill","Skill","Diana","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Diana's Crescent Strike into Pale Cascade all-in is one of the strongest early kill patterns in mid lane, and if she lands the moon slow you're in serious trouble before your kit fully comes online."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Moonfall lets Diana pull you in and reset her Pale Cascade shield for a devastating all-in — this is her best window to force a fight and she should take it whenever she can."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Once you finish your first item spike your burst combo starts to edge out her sustained-fight damage, especially if you can dodge her Crescent Strike."},{"when":"Late","text":"Chronobreak gives you the safety net to flank and burst her down in skirmishes, while her all-in potential without a landed Crescent Strike drops off relative to your scaling threat."}],"wants":{"you":["Play safe around minions to avoid a clean Crescent Strike hit","Look to punish her when Crescent Strike is on cooldown","Save Chronobreak for late-game flank opportunities in side fights"],"foe":["Land Crescent Strike to guarantee the slow into all-in","Use Moonfall to reset Pale Cascade mid-fight for extra burst","Force all-ins at level 6 before Ekko's own spike arrives"]},"early":"This lane is a coinflip on her landed Crescent Strike — if she hits it, the slow plus Pale Cascade all-in is nearly impossible to escape, but if she misses you can safely punish her with poke and zone her off farm, so level 1-2 comes down to whether she lands her skillshot.","mid":"Diana keeps the edge through level 6 with Moonfall giving her a guaranteed engage tool to pull you in and reset her shield for a full burst combo, so you need to respect her all-in range until your own kit and Chronobreak catch up.","late":"Once you've got your first item and Chronobreak available, you finally have the tools to dodge her engage and burst her in return — her kill pattern depends on landing Crescent Strike first, and your rewind safety net means a whiffed engage from her can get punished hard.","whys":["Whether Diana lands Crescent Strike is the coinflip that decides early trades, making this phase even.","Diana's all-in with Pale Cascade shielding is a genuine kill threat if she lands her slow, favouring her.","Neither side has a clean edge here — you can punish missed Crescent Strikes but she still threatens all-ins.","Diana's overall early trading pattern and shield sustain keep her ahead through the laning phase.","Moonfall gives Diana a guaranteed pull-in engage at level 6, making this her strongest all-in window.","Your item spike plus Chronobreak safety net finally lets you punish her engage attempts and win fights.","Late game your rewind-enabled dive potential outpaces her all-in-or-nothing kit when she whiffs her engage."]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"fizz","win":["Skill","Skill","Skill","Skill","Ekko","Fizz","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Both champs are volatile skirmishers early — Fizz's Seastone Trident poke and Playful/Trickster untargetability trade evenly against your own Q-W poke pattern, so early trades come down to who lands first."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Chronobreak beats Playful/Trickster's untargetability in a straight duel — you can rewind through his dive and punish him even after he jumps you, so your all-in window at 6 is genuinely strong."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Fizz's burst spike with a completed core item (like Riftmaker or Nashor's) briefly out-trades you if he lands Chum the Waters, since the slow guarantees his full combo connects."},{"when":"Late","text":"Your Chronobreak safety net and superior wave-clear pressure make you the better teamfight flanker once both sides are itemized, since Fizz's all-in depends entirely on connecting Trickster into you."}],"wants":{"you":["Trade evenly early and watch for Fizz's Trickster jump timing","Save Chronobreak to punish his all-in dives at level 6","Use your wave-clear to force him into unfavorable side-lane fights"],"foe":["Land Chum the Waters to guarantee his full burst combo connects","Use Playful/Trickster to dodge your engage and reset the fight","Punish you the moment his item spike gives him lethal burst"]},"early":"This lane is a genuine skill matchup — Fizz's Seastone Trident poke and slippery Trickster jump make him hard to pin down, while your own Q-W trades and wave pressure keep things even, so neither side has a clear edge until levels 4-5 shake out based on who executes better.","mid":"Level 6 flips clearly in your favor: Chronobreak lets you rewind through a Playful/Trickster dive and punish Fizz even after he thinks he's escaped, giving you the safer and stronger all-in window, though his own itemized burst spike briefly claws back an edge right when his first core item completes.","late":"Once you're both fully online, your Chronobreak dive potential and better wave control let you flank and burst him down in skirmishes, while his own all-in depends on landing Chum the Waters cleanly — a much harder ask into a champion who can simply rewind away from a bad engage.","whys":["Both champs trade fairly evenly at level 1-2, with poke and mobility roughly canceling out — a genuine skill matchup.","Trading patterns remain close through level 3, with neither Fizz's poke nor your combo securing a clear lead.","This phase stays even as both sides look for good all-in windows without a decisive damage or mobility edge.","Levels 4-5 remain a coinflip based on execution rather than raw kit advantage for either side.","Chronobreak gives you a genuine edge at level 6, letting you rewind through his dive and punish him back.","Fizz's completed item spike briefly gives him the burst edge if he lands his slow before you can react.","Your superior late-game flank potential with Chronobreak and wave control makes you the stronger teamfighter overall."]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"galio","win":["Skill","Skill","Galio","Skill","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Galio's Winds of War and Shield of Durand punish extended trades — if you overstay in melee range he taunts your engage away with Justice Punch, giving him a strong short window."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Chronobreak is a far more flexible ultimate than Hero's Entrance for solo-lane impact — Galio's ult is built for roaming and peeling, not winning the 1v1, so your ultimate spike matters more here."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Once you finish your burst item you can punish his low base damage output — Galio is built to tank and disrupt, not to out-trade you once your combo does real damage."},{"when":"Late","text":"Your burst potential with Chronobreak safety net wins skirmishes clean, since Galio's kit is entirely about peel and disruption for teammates rather than dueling you directly."}],"wants":{"you":["Avoid overextending into his Justice Punch taunt range","Punish his low damage output once your first item lands","Bait Shield of Durand on cooldown before committing to trades"],"foe":["Land Justice Punch to taunt and disrupt your combo mid-fight","Use Winds of War to zone you off farm and poke safely","Save Hero's Entrance to roam and swing other lanes instead of dueling"]},"early":"Early trades are fairly balanced — Galio's Winds of War poke and passive resistances make him tanky, but his damage is genuinely low for a mid laner, so you can generally match him in short trades as long as you respect his Justice Punch taunt range around minions.","mid":"Levels 3-5 briefly tilt toward Galio if he lands a taunt into a full combo, since Shield of Durand's damage reduction lets him win a prolonged trade you'd otherwise take, but by level 6 your Chronobreak gives you a far stronger duel tool than his roam-oriented ultimate, flipping momentum clearly back to you.","late":"Late game Galio functions almost entirely as a peel and initiation tool for his team rather than a duelist, so once your burst item comes online you comfortably out-damage him in any 1v1 or pick situation, with Chronobreak giving you the safety to force those fights on your terms.","whys":["Early trades are close to even — Galio's tankiness offsets his low damage, and neither side has landed a clear window yet.","This phase stays balanced as both champions poke cautiously without a decisive damage or mobility edge.","Galio's Justice Punch taunt into a full combo gives him a real edge if he lands it during this window.","Levels 4-5 remain roughly even as you trade cautiously around his taunt range and disruption tools.","Your burst potential plus Chronobreak's dueling value clearly outclasses Galio's team-oriented ultimate at level 6.","Galio's kit is built for peeling and roaming, not dueling, so your item spike lets you win 1v1s cleanly here.","Late game your damage output and safety net from Chronobreak keep you ahead of a champion with minimal personal burst."]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"hwei","win":["Ekko","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Hwei's Devastating Fire and Severing Bolt poke require precise setups, but he's extremely squishy and immobile early, so once your combo is online you can punish any misplaced cast with a hard all-in."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Chronobreak lets you completely ignore Hwei's Countenance combos — his ultimate is a zoning and pick tool, not a duel-winner, and your rewind means his attempts to root or fear you rarely land clean kills."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Your burst item spike lets you close the gap on Hwei before his long-cast-time spells fully punish you, since he has zero mobility to escape once you're in melee range."},{"when":"Late","text":"Even at full build Hwei's damage is scary at range, but his total lack of any dash or blink means your dive-and-rewind pattern with Chronobreak keeps punishing him in every skirmish."}],"wants":{"you":["Close the gap fast and punish his lack of any escape tool","Dodge his Fated Painting combos and all-in when he whiffs","Use Chronobreak to guarantee a kill once you're in melee range"],"foe":["Poke you down with Severing Bolt and Devastating Fire from max range","Land a rooting Fated Painting combo to lock you down","Kite backward using terrain, since he has no dash of his own"]},"early":"You're ahead from level 1 — Hwei's combos require precise, telegraphed setups across two canvases, and if he ever whiffs a key spell you can close the distance immediately and punish him hard, since he has zero mobility to disengage once you're on top of him.","mid":"This lead only widens at level 6: Chronobreak makes his best all-in tools, which rely on landing hard crowd control to secure a kill, essentially non-threatening, because you can rewind out of a bad position or dive back in once he's used his combo.","late":"Even with a completed build and genuinely scary poke damage, Hwei has no dash, blink, or any form of true mobility, so your dive-and-rewind kit continues to punish him in skirmishes and picks throughout the entire game.","whys":["Hwei's lack of mobility and reliance on landing setup spells means you punish him hard in early trades.","You continue to snowball as your combo comes online while Hwei still has no way to escape a committed engage.","Your pressure keeps compounding since any missed combo from Hwei gets punished immediately by your dive.","Levels 4-5 remain firmly in your favor as your all-in threat outpaces his ability to zone you from range.","Chronobreak completely undercuts Hwei's kill windows, since his crowd control needs to land cleanly to matter.","Your dive potential continues to dominate as his ultimate is built for zoning and picks, not dueling you directly.","Hwei's total lack of mobility means even at full build your dive-and-rewind pattern keeps him on the back foot."]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"irelia","win":["Skill","Skill","Skill","Skill","Irelia","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Irelia's stun-reset all-in with Bladesurge into Ionian Fervor spikes hard once she hits two items' worth of Q resets on minions, but pre-6 she still has to walk in through your Timewinder zone, so trades stay even if you respect her all-in range."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Irelia's kit doesn't get a hard power spike from her ult the way most mid laners do — Vanguard's Edge is more of a peel/dive tool — so this is where her all-in timing on you actually tightens up thanks to level-6 Ionian Fervor stacking, not an ultimate check."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Once Ekko finishes a core item and has Parallel Convergence up on cooldown rotation, you out-scale her lane all-in completely — she has no way to burst you down before your stun locks her in place."},{"when":"Late","text":"Late game Irelia becomes a split-push/dive threat but has almost no answer to your Chronobreak reset in skirmishes, and Z-Drive Resonance shreds her through her passive shield stacking."}],"wants":{"you":["Farm safely under tower early and avoid extended trades into her Q resets","Save Parallel Convergence to punish her overextending on a Bladesurge reset attempt","Look for roams once you have Phase Dive range advantage and she's committed to farming"],"foe":["Stack minion Q resets to burst you down before 6","Force all-in trades in the pre-6 window when her Ionian Fervor stacks are cheap","Use Bladesurge to dodge your stun setup and go all-in off cooldown"]},"early":"Levels 1-2 are a stalemate: Irelia's Bladesurge poke costs her mana and resets are inconsistent on cannon-less waves, while your own Timewinder harass is on a long cooldown, so both sides mostly just farm and watch for overextensions.","mid":"Levels 3-4 favor Irelia if she gets clean Q resets off minions to true-damage-proc into an all-in, but by level 5 her ability to just walk you down fades since your Parallel Convergence threat zone covers your farm; level 6 flips fully your way because Ekko's Ionian Fervor-adjusted power curve catches up and she has no ultimate spike to counter your Chronobreak setup.","late":"With one item Ekko wins any 1v1 outright — Z-Drive Resonance plus your reset punishes her dueling, and in teamfights Chronobreak lets you rewind a bad engage while she's stuck fighting at the front with no true escape.","whys":["Level 1 is an even skill-matchup — neither champion has a hard poke or all-in tool online yet, so trades are decided by who plays the lane better.","Level 2 stays skill-based since Irelia's second Q reset chain isn't guaranteed on a non-cannon wave, keeping the exchange close.","Level 3 is still a skill check — Irelia's all-in window opens but Ekko can dodge it with proper Timewinder positioning, so outcome depends on execution.","Level 4 remains even for the same reason — her damage output is scaling but not yet overwhelming, and Ekko's kit is coming online too.","Levels 4-5 tip to Irelia because her Ionian Fervor stacking plus cheap Q resets let her force all-ins Ekko can't yet answer with a reliable stun.","Level 6 swings to Ekko since Chronobreak gives you a genuine escape/reset tool while Irelia's ultimate offers no comparable burst spike, letting your base kit catch up.","With first item, Ekko clearly wins — Parallel Convergence lockdown plus Z-Drive Resonance burst outclasses anything Irelia can answer with at the same gold value."]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"karma","win":["Skill","Skill","Karma","Karma","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Karma's Mantra-empowered Soulflare (RQ) becomes available around level 3-5 giving her a big root-and-burn poke combo that punishes any greedy CS animation, this is her strongest poke window before Ekko has enough combat stats to trade back."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Ekko's actual level 6 doesn't add a burst spike over Karma's mantra combo, but it does give you Chronobreak as an escape from her long-range root chain, and from here your base kit's damage starts to outpace her poke-only kit."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Once you finish a first item, Ekko's all-in via Phase Dive plus Z-Drive Resonance easily out-trades Karma's remaining mana-hungry poke, especially since she has no hard CC beyond the Soulflare root to punish your engage."},{"when":"Late","text":"Late game Karma becomes support-shaped (utility, shields, wave clear) but her low base damage means Ekko simply one-shots her in skirmishes if you land Parallel Convergence, especially once she's used Mantra defensively on an ally."}],"wants":{"you":["Play patient early and avoid walking into Soulflare root range without minions to soak it","Track her Mantra charge state — Q-Mantra roots hurt, but the empowered E shield removes your all-in windows","Look to roam once she's used Mantra on a bot lane play, since her lane pressure drops"],"foe":["Land Mantra-Q roots to zone you off CS and chip your HP down","Use empowered W speed shield to disengage or reposition to safety, then punish overextensions","Push freezes and force short trades using Soulflare's burn while denying you farm"]},"early":"Levels 1-2 are close and skill-dependent — Karma's base Q poke is real but telegraphed, and Ekko can still farm through it if you respect her range; neither side has a combo online yet so it comes down to who lands more pokes cleanly.","mid":"Levels 3-4 clearly favor Karma once Mantra unlocks Soulflare, since the root-into-burn combo punishes any CS attempt and she can zone you off half the wave without real retaliation; by level 6 the tide turns because Ekko's kit finally has enough base damage and Chronobreak safety to start pressuring back despite her having no true ultimate spike of her own.","late":"With one item Ekko simply outclasses Karma in any direct confrontation — her kit caps out as utility and poke with no scaling burst, while your Z-Drive Resonance and reset let you delete her before her shields matter.","whys":["Level 1 is an even skill matchup — Karma's poke exists but is avoidable, so early trades reward good CS positioning from both sides.","Level 2 stays skill-based for the same reason — no combo is online yet, it's a battle of who lands clean pokes.","Level 3 favors Karma outright since her Mantra-Soulflare root-burn combo comes online and Ekko has no comparable answer at this level.","Level 4 stays Karma-favored as she continues to abuse the Soulflare combo on cooldown to zone you off farm and chip your health.","Level 5 flips to Ekko because your base kit's damage and mobility start catching up while Karma's combo cooldown can't keep pace with her lack of scaling.","Level 6 favors Ekko since Chronobreak gives you safety from her root chain and her ultimate offers no burst spike to counter your growing power.","With first item, Ekko is clearly ahead — your all-in burst overwhelms Karma's poke-and-utility kit which has nothing to punish you back with at equal gold."]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"kassadin","win":["Skill","Skill","Skill","Skill","Ekko","Ekko","Kassadin"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Both champions are mana- and item-dependent scalers in this window, so trades stay skill-based — Kassadin's Nether Blade proc and Riftwalk chaining are still weak due to mana costs, and Ekko's Timewinder poke is on a long cooldown, so neither side can force a clean advantage."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Ekko's Chronobreak reset gives you a real edge over Kassadin's early Riftslash all-in since he's still mana-starved on his own ultimate, letting Ekko punish any overextension with a rewind before he scales into the matchup's real threat."},{"when":"1st item","text":"With a first item and mana sustain from a Tear component, Kassadin's Riftwalk-chain burst starts to threaten Ekko hard, especially since Riftwalk lets him blink onto you unpredictably and his passive magic resist shrugs off your Z-Drive Resonance damage."},{"when":"Late","text":"Late game Kassadin fully takes over the matchup — with a completed Nether Blade item and mana from Seraph's/Tear, he can chain 2-3 Riftwalks to burst and reposition faster than Ekko can react, and his silence on R shuts down your Chronobreak escape entirely."}],"wants":{"you":["Punish Kassadin hard before level 9 while his mana pool can't support Riftwalk spam","Deny him easy CS so he falls behind on the mana items he desperately needs","Bank Parallel Convergence for his all-in windows once he starts chaining Riftwalk"],"foe":["Farm safely and avoid all trades until Riftwalk mana costs become manageable","Rush a mana item to unlock double/triple Riftwalk combos","Time his ultimate's silence to shut down your Chronobreak the moment he all-ins"]},"early":"Levels 1-2 stay even and skill-based since both champions are weak in lane — Kassadin has no ultimate and costly abilities, while Ekko's own combo is clunky without levels, so trades hinge on who dodges skillshots and manages minion aggro better.","mid":"Levels 3-5 remain a coinflip on skill — Kassadin's kit is still too mana-hungry to punish you consistently and your Timewinder isn't hitting hard enough yet either, but once level 6 arrives Ekko gets a genuine window: your Chronobreak reset lets you play aggressively into his still-weak Riftwalk before he's scaled into it.","late":"Once Kassadin finishes his mana item and reaches late game, the matchup flips hard in his favor — his Riftwalk chains outpace your mobility, his magic resistance blunts your burst, and his R-silence can lock down your Chronobreak at the worst possible moment.","whys":["Level 1 is an even skill matchup — both champions are weak and mana-limited, so trading is about precision, not kit power.","Level 2 stays skill-based for the same reasons — neither side has unlocked a real power spike yet.","Level 3 remains even since Kassadin's Q/W combo is still too costly to spam and Ekko's own combo isn't fully online either.","Level 4 stays a skill matchup as both kits continue scaling at similar rates without a clear advantage either way.","Level 5 is still skill-dependent — right before Kassadin's ultimate unlocks, the lane hinges on trade discipline rather than raw power.","Level 6 favors Ekko because Chronobreak gives you a safety net to punish his still mana-starved Riftwalk, while his own ultimate isn't strong enough yet to flip it back.","Late game favors Kassadin outright since his scaled Riftwalk chains, magic resistance, and silence completely outclass Ekko's tools at equal gold."]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"katarina","win":["Skill","Katarina","Katarina","Skill","Katarina","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Katarina's Death Lotus isn't even out yet at 3-5, but her Bouncing Blade-into-Sinister Steel reset chain lets her deal huge burst off a single dagger throw, and her Shunpo blink onto low-HP daggers punishes any careless poke trade from Ekko."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Once Death Lotus unlocks, Katarina threatens a full lane kill if she can land Bouncing Blade first — the channel is real damage even if interrupted, and she can Shunpo away from your stun setup mid-channel, though this is also right when your own Chronobreak comes online to punish her if she misses her opener."},{"when":"1st item","text":"With a first item, Ekko's Parallel Convergence stun finally lines up reliably with your Z-Drive Resonance burst, letting you punish Katarina's all-in attempts before she can reset off a kill, flipping the trade in your favor."},{"when":"Late","text":"Late game Ekko clearly wins extended fights — Katarina is a one-shot-or-die assassin with no escape besides Shunpo resets, and once you land your stun she has no way out of your combo, while she needs picks to stay relevant."}],"wants":{"you":["Play safe around minion waves so she can't Shunpo off a low-HP dagger onto you","Save Parallel Convergence for her all-in dive rather than using it to poke","Look to snowball a lead into item power since you outscale her 1-for-1 later"],"foe":["Land Bouncing Blade on you directly to set up a Shunpo gap-close and burst combo","Reset E cooldown off minion/dagger bounces to chain damage before you can react","All-in during her Death Lotus channel window and use Shunpo to dodge your stun"]},"early":"Level 1 is close and skill-based since neither side has a full combo, but from levels 2-3 Katarina's dagger-bounce reset chain starts punishing any trade where Ekko gets hit by Bouncing Blade, letting her snowball kills off good positioning.","mid":"Levels 3-5 stay Katarina-favored as her burst combo scales faster than Ekko's, and level 6 is still her window since Death Lotus threatens a full kill if she opens correctly — though this is also the point where your Chronobreak starts giving you a real punish tool if she misses her engage.","late":"Once Ekko has a first item, the matchup flips hard — Parallel Convergence locks her down before she can reset off you, and in late-game skirmishes your reset and burst clearly outclass her all-or-nothing assassin kit.","whys":["Level 1 is an even skill matchup — neither champion has combo pieces online, so it comes down to careful trading and dodging skillshots.","Level 2 favors Katarina because her Bouncing Blade-Shunpo reset chain starts punishing any hit landed on Ekko, letting her snowball small trades into bigger ones.","Level 3 stays Katarina-favored as her combo damage keeps scaling faster than Ekko's own kit at this point in the level curve.","Level 4 is an even skill matchup again as Ekko's kit catches up in raw damage, making trades come down to who executes cleaner.","Level 5 favors Katarina since her all-in burst window right before ultimate access still outpaces what Ekko can answer with.","Level 6 favors Ekko because Chronobreak gives you a way to survive and punish her Death Lotus all-in attempt if she doesn't open perfectly.","With first item, Ekko clearly wins — your stun-into-burst combo finally out-trades her reset chain before she can capitalize on a kill."]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"leblanc","win":["Skill","LeBlanc","LeBlanc","LeBlanc","LeBlanc","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"LeBlanc's Sigil of Malice into Distortion combo becomes a genuine all-in threat around level 3, letting her chain a root and burst with a Mimic reset that Ekko simply can't answer until his own kit scales up."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"With Mimic unlocked, LeBlanc can double-cast her full combo for a burst window that threatens to delete Ekko outright if she catches you out of position, and her Distortion blink-back makes her nearly unpunishable even after committing."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Ekko's first item finally gives you the damage and mobility to punish LeBlanc's cooldowns — once her Distortion and Sigil are down, your Phase Dive engage plus Parallel Convergence stun lets you win a straight fight she can no longer escape."},{"when":"Late","text":"Late game LeBlanc falls off hard as a pure burst mage with no scaling utility, while Ekko's Z-Drive Resonance and Chronobreak give you sustained skirmish presence and a kill-securing reset she has no way to counter."}],"wants":{"you":["Play passively around minions early to avoid getting rooted by Sigil of Malice combos","Track her Distortion cooldown so you know when she's actually vulnerable to an all-in","Look to punish her hard once her first item timer passes and yours catches up"],"foe":["Land Sigil of Malice to root you, then chain Distortion-Q for a full burst combo","Use Mimic post-6 to double the combo and threaten a full kill in one rotation","Blink away with Distortion's return cast to escape any retaliation risk-free"]},"early":"Level 1 is close and skill-based as neither side has full combos, but from level 3 onward LeBlanc's Sigil-root into Distortion burst starts punishing Ekko hard, and this pressure only intensifies at level 6 once Mimic lets her double the combo for a potential kill.","mid":"Levels 3 through 6 are LeBlanc's window entirely — her root-into-burst combo plus a safe Distortion blink-out means Ekko has no reliable way to punish her aggression, and Mimic access at 6 makes her all-in even scarier since she can double the combo for a genuine kill threat.","late":"Once Ekko has a first item, the tables turn hard — her burst falls behind your scaling, your stun finally lands cleanly on her approach, and by late game she has no sustained presence to match your reset-enabled skirmishing.","whys":["Level 1 is an even skill matchup — neither champion has their full combo online, so trades hinge on positioning and wave management.","Level 2 favors LeBlanc since her Sigil-Distortion root-and-burst combo starts coming together, letting her punish any overextension from Ekko.","Level 3 stays LeBlanc-favored as the combo damage scales up further while Ekko still lacks the tools to answer it.","Level 4 remains LeBlanc's window for the same reason — her burst keeps outpacing Ekko's growth at this stage.","Levels 4-5 continue to favor LeBlanc as she can safely poke and burst using Distortion's blink-back with little risk of retaliation.","Level 6 favors LeBlanc since Mimic lets her double her burst combo for a genuine kill threat, and Ekko's own Chronobreak isn't enough yet to offset that raw damage spike.","With first item, Ekko clearly wins — once her key cooldowns are down, your engage and stun overwhelm her lack of sustained follow-up."]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"lissandra","win":["Skill","Skill","Skill","Skill","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Lissandra's Ice Shard-Claw poke plus a well-timed Glacial Path root gives her real trading power in this window, but her low base damage and Ekko's own Timewinder poke keep the exchange close and skill-dependent rather than one-sided."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Ekko's Chronobreak comes online right as Lissandra's own ultimate is more of a peel/save tool than a lane-kill button, so this is where Ekko's kit starts to pull ahead — you can dive her all-in attempts and reset out if she oversteps."},{"when":"1st item","text":"With a first item, Ekko's burst from Z-Drive Resonance plus Parallel Convergence outpaces Lissandra's poke-based damage output, and her Ice Shard root alone isn't enough to stop your all-in once you're in range."},{"when":"Late","text":"Late game Lissandra shifts into a teamfight peel/CC support-mage role while Ekko remains a genuine skirmish threat — your reset and burst let you punish her positioning far more than her kit can punish yours."}],"wants":{"you":["Trade evenly early and avoid overextending into her Glacial Path root range","Watch her Claw Marks stacks before committing to an all-in, since empowered damage hurts","Look to snowball a lead post-6 since Chronobreak gives you the safer all-in tool"],"foe":["Poke with Ice Shard and empowered Claw Marks auto to whittle Ekko's HP from range","Use Glacial Path to root and follow with a combo when Ekko misplays positioning","Save her ultimate defensively to freeze incoming ganks or all-ins rather than force kills"]},"early":"Levels 1-4 stay close and skill-based — Lissandra's poke is real but her low base damage means Ekko can trade back evenly if you dodge her root, and neither champion has a clean burst window yet to force a decisive advantage.","mid":"Level 5 remains an even skill matchup as both kits are still scaling similarly, but level 6 flips clearly to Ekko since Chronobreak gives you a much safer and stronger all-in tool than her defensive-leaning ultimate, letting you start pressuring her more aggressively.","late":"With items, Ekko clearly wins skirmishes — Lissandra's kit trends toward peel and utility in teamfights while your burst-and-reset combo lets you punish her positioning directly whenever she's caught without her ultimate up.","whys":["Level 1 is an even skill matchup — Lissandra's poke exists but her damage is too low this early to force a real advantage, so trading rewards careful play from both.","Level 2 stays skill-based for the same reason — neither side has a combo strong enough to punish good CS positioning.","Level 3 remains even as Lissandra's Glacial Path root becomes threatening but is still dodgeable, keeping the exchange close.","Level 4 is still a skill matchup since both champions are scaling at a similar rate without either pulling ahead.","Level 5 stays even as the last stretch before ultimates — trades still depend on execution rather than kit power.","Level 6 favors Ekko because Chronobreak is a genuinely strong all-in and escape tool while Lissandra's ultimate is built more for peel than punishing Ekko directly.","With first item, Ekko clearly wins — your burst and reset outclass her poke-based damage profile in any direct confrontation."]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"locke","win":["Skill","Skill","Skill","Skill","Skill","Skill","Skill"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"With no meaningful sample data on this matchup, treat the early-mid window as a standard skill check — play around your Timewinder cooldown and punish any obvious overextension the same way you would against an unfamiliar mid laner."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Ekko's Chronobreak is one of the best reset tools in the mid lane roster regardless of matchup, so treat level 6 as your first chance to force a decisive all-in if you've been trading evenly up to this point."},{"when":"1st item","text":"By first item, default to your normal power spike assumptions — Ekko's Z-Drive Resonance burst plus Parallel Convergence stun is strong into most skill-matchup mid laners, so look to snowball if the lane has stayed close."},{"when":"Late","text":"Late game, fall back on Ekko's core identity — a skirmish and pick-oriented mage with a reset that lets you fight and disengage more freely than most mid laners, which tends to close out even lanes in your favor."}],"wants":{"you":["Play the matchup like a standard unknown lane — respect unfamiliar combos until you see them once","Bank Parallel Convergence for a confirmed all-in window rather than using it speculatively","Look to leverage Chronobreak's reset for greedy trades once you have vision on cooldowns"],"foe":["Play to whatever core combo or poke tool defines their kit, since no specific data exists here","Look for early trades before Ekko's kit comes online at level 6","Punish any Ekko misplay around minion wave positioning"]},"early":"With no recorded games for this matchup, levels 1-5 should be played as a generic even lane — trade cautiously, learn the opponent's cooldowns in real time, and don't commit to all-ins until you understand their kit.","mid":"Level 6 onward, default to Ekko's normal strengths: Chronobreak gives you a safety net and all-in tool that's strong regardless of opponent, so this is typically where you start looking to press an advantage if the lane has been neutral.","late":"Lategame favor Ekko's core game plan — burst, reset, and roam — since as a flexible skirmisher your kit tends to close out even matchups in your favor once you have item power.","whys":["Level 1 has no reliable data, so it's treated as an even skill matchup where lane fundamentals decide trades.","Level 2 is likewise undetermined and treated as skill-based — neither side has a proven edge.","Level 3 remains a skill matchup by default since no meaningful sample exists to suggest either side has a kit advantage.","Level 4 stays even for the same reason — insufficient data to color this phase either way.","Level 5 is treated as even since no combo or power-spike data distinguishes this matchup at this stage.","Level 6 is marked as a skill matchup since Ekko's Chronobreak is strong in general, but without specific data this remains a neutral call rather than a confirmed favor.","First item is treated as even by default — Ekko's core itemized power spike is strong broadly, but with no matchup-specific data this stays a skill-based phase."]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"lux","win":["Ekko","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Once you have Q-W available together you can zone Lux out of easy poke range by threatening the boomerang return burst on any overextension."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Chronobreak lets you shrug off a Final Spark all-in attempt and punish her for using R offensively."},{"when":"1st item","text":"With one full item your Q-AA-E combo one-shots a squishy Lux who mispositions near minions or the W zone."},{"when":"Late","text":"Full combo plus R sustain means Lux has no answer if she's caught alone; she must play entirely around vision and peel."}],"wants":{"you":["Dodge Q sideways, never walk straight at her","Hide in minion waves so W/E landing spots are unclear","Punish every Q miss with an immediate all-in"],"foe":["Land Q from max range to zone your approach","Kite backward using minions as Q/AA blockers","Save Shield (E) for your all-in window"]},"early":"Lux's Q is the whole lane: if she lands it you lose half your HP bar and your trade window, so hug minions and change your walk pattern constantly. Your own poke is worse than hers at level 1-2, so don't trade into a landed Q — just farm and reset. Around level 3 you get W online, but it's slow and telegraphed, so use it defensively to block her all-in rather than offensively. Watch for her E-Q combo near the bush; if she flashes it you're likely dead before level 6.","mid":"From level 3 onward, bait her Q by faking a walk-up then punishing the miss with Q-E-AA. Level 6 flips the lane hard: her Final Spark all-in into your death is now the thing that gets her killed, since Chronobreak heals you off the damage and can burst her back. Roam together with jungle when she pushes to farm from range; she has zero mobility to escape a 2-man dive. Track her ult cooldown (roughly 20s+) — punish the window right after she uses it on a wave or a roam.","late":"With Sorcerer's Shoes/Zhonya first-item power, Ekko two-shots Lux through most peel if he lands E onto her — flanking through fog or via Zhonya-timing her Q is the standard kill pattern. Ekko becomes the primary pick-threat in teamfights: dive on cooldown-Lux, use R to reset position after the burst, and never walk into her Q sightline in the open. Lux's only real out is layered peel (Zhonya, knockups, exhaust) — if her team can't provide that, she dies to any Ekko flank.","whys":["Level 1: neither has combat power yet, but Lux's Q range means she dictates the trade, not you.","Level 2: your second point barely changes your all-in threat while her poke keeps landing for free.","Level 3: W comes online but is too slow to punish her poke in real time, so it's still her lane to press.","Levels 4-5: you can finally threaten burst off a dodged Q, clawing the lane back toward even.","Level 6: Chronobreak turns her all-in attempts into her own death sentence, flipping the matchup to you.","First item: your combo one-shot potential outpaces her scaling utility kit, making short trades lethal.","2+ items: full build Ekko out-damages and out-mobilizes a stationary mage with no escape."]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"malzahar","win":["Skill","Skill","Malzahar","Skill","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Malzahar's Voidlings and passive shield push you off the wave for free, so this stretch is about minimizing lost CS, not fighting him."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Malefic Visions plus Nether Grasp lets him delete you from range the moment he hits 6, well before your own R matters much."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Your first full item combo finally threatens to punish him if he oversteps into E range, though his passive shield still blunts the burst."},{"when":"Late","text":"Once you can flank through fog and dodge his skillshot-free suppress by baiting Zhonya or R timing, your burst and R sustain start to outpace his DoT."}],"wants":{"you":["Farm from max range with Q, avoid melee exchanges","Buy MR/Merc Treads early to blunt his true-damage-ish DoT and suppress burst","Wait for a misplay or vision gap before diving; never walk into his E range blind"],"foe":["Push wave hard with Voidlings, deny CS","Land E on any melee approach to zone you off farm","Look for R+combo kill once you hit 6 and he has a full rotation"]},"early":"Malzahar's Voidlings auto-push the wave and his passive shields him from your poke, so trying to trade Q into him early just feeds his shield back into his face. Respect his E (Malefic Visions) range completely — it does real damage over time and reveals you, setting up ganks. Levels 1-2 are close to unplayable proactively; just last-hit under turret and hold Timewinder for peeling Voidlings off the wave. Don't group up in melee range for AA trades — his passive punishes exactly that.","mid":"Level 6 is Malzahar's biggest spike in the whole game: Nether Grasp suppress into full combo can delete you from near-max range with no counterplay besides Cleanse or a body-block. Play very safe around 6, holding Flash/QSS mentally and staying behind minions so he can't get a clean channel angle. Your own combo starts threatening real damage around level 9-11 with points in Q/E, but you still need him to misstep into dive range since his push forces you into an awkward position most of the trades. Look to roam when he's shoving the wave into your tower — he has no way to punish you leaving.","late":"With a full-item Ekko, your one-shot combo (Q-E-AA-W re-entry) can burst him down if you catch him without his suppress or Zhonya available, and Chronobreak lets you dive-and-reset through his DoT damage that would otherwise kill a squishier assassin. The matchup remains volatile because his R is a hard suppress with no skill-shot counterplay — you must flank from fog/bushes rather than approach head-on, or bait his R onto a decoy. If your team has peel/dive support to force him to use R early in a fight, Ekko cleans up everything behind it.","whys":["Level 1: his Voidlings auto-shove and shield him, giving him free lane control from minute one.","Level 2: same push pattern continues, you're purely reacting and preserving CS.","Level 3: his passive shield hard-counters your early poke attempts, letting him press even harder.","Levels 4-5: still his lane — Voidling pressure plus E zone denies your window to punish.","Level 6: his suppress-combo one-shot threat range is simply scarier than your ult at this stage.","First item: your burst starts threatening him back, but his shield and DoT still make trades close.","2+ items: your flank-burst-R kit finally out-damages his sustained pressure once you play around his suppress."]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"mel","win":["Mel","Mel","Skill","Skill","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Mel's beam poke and reflect passive still out-trade your early kit, so this stretch stays roughly even at best while you farm carefully."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Chronobreak's reposition-plus-heal lets you shrug off a poke-heavy all-in and finally threaten a real kill window on her."},{"when":"1st item","text":"A full burst item lets your all-in combo outrace her reflect-shield uptime if you catch her poke on cooldown."},{"when":"Late","text":"Fully itemized, your flank speed and burst chunk her before her passive shield or peel can reset the fight."}],"wants":{"you":["Farm from angles that block her beam, use minions as cover","Track her passive reflect-shield cooldown before committing E","Save all-ins for the window right after she uses a key spell"],"foe":["Poke you down safely from range with her beam","Punish overextensions before your combo is fully online","Kite using her reflect passive to blunt your engage damage"]},"early":"Mel's ranged poke and damage-reflecting passive make early trades expensive for you, since dashing in with E to auto-reset just feeds free damage back onto you. Play a patient farming lane through levels 1-2, using minion bodies to block her line and only stepping up to last-hit when her poke is on cooldown. Levels 3-5 are still tilted her way — she out-ranges your entire early kit and her reflect makes short trades a loss even when you land Q. Hold your all-in ambitions until you have level 6 and real item damage.","mid":"Level 6 is where Ekko starts clawing the lane back: Chronobreak lets you tank an extra poke rotation and then punish her for over-committing, since the heal offsets a big chunk of her ranged damage. Look for windows right after she uses her defensive tools or pushes too far for a wave — that's when your dash-AA-Q combo can land clean without eating a reflected hit. Continue playing patiently otherwise; her poke uptime is still higher than your sustained pressure until your first full item lands.","late":"Once you have burst damage online, your flank speed via E and R reposition let you dictate the engage rather than walking into her preferred poke range, and a landed full combo can drop her before her reflect shield resets. In teamfights, look to flank from side lanes/fog rather than approaching head-on into her beam, since a clean read-free engage bypasses her strongest tool. If her team can peel or she plays purely reactive, the fight stays close, but an isolated Mel dies fast to a full-item Ekko all-in.","whys":["Level 1: her ranged poke tool already out-trades anything you can offer at rank 1.","Level 2: same story — she keeps chipping you down while your kit is still too weak to answer.","Level 3: your W comes online but is too slow to punish her poke pattern in real time.","Levels 4-5: her reflect passive keeps blunting your trades, so the lane stays in her favor.","Level 6: Chronobreak's sustain and reposition finally let you contest her poke uptime.","First item: your burst combo starts to outrace her reflect-shield cooldown when timed well.","2+ items: full burst plus flank mobility lets you punish her before her kit can reset the exchange."]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"naafiri","win":["Skill","Naafiri","Naafiri","Naafiri","Naafiri","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Naafiri's pack of pseudo-minions and dash resets let her all-in and win extended trades well before your combo is strong enough to answer."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Chronobreak finally gives you an escape and counter-burst to punish her all-in the moment she over-commits."},{"when":"1st item","text":"With core damage online your W-punish and Q burst start threatening to actually kill her back if she dives without vision of your combo."},{"when":"Late","text":"Your zone-control W plus flank tools let you dictate engages instead of getting run down, tipping extended fights back your way."}],"wants":{"you":["Ward and ping her pack dashes so you're never caught alone","Play behind minions early, avoid extended melee trades","Use W defensively to punish her all-in once she commits"],"foe":["Snowball early kills with pack-assisted all-ins","Chain dashes to keep you locked down before your kit is online","Force short trades where her early damage wins outright"]},"early":"Naafiri's early game is built to bully exactly this kind of matchup — her pack members and dash resets give her far more sustained pressure and burst than your kit has access to before level 6. Levels 1-2 you should play passively, never trading extended, since her all-in just deletes you if she commits. Levels 3-5 remain rough: her dashes chain together faster than your kit can punish, and getting caught out of position near her pack means a dead Ekko. Ward the flanks so she can't set up an unseen all-in, and lean on your jungler for early tempo.","mid":"Level 6 is your turning point: Chronobreak gives you a genuine answer to her all-in pattern, letting you rewind out of a bad engage or punish her over-commit with a counter-burst. Until your first item, though, still avoid initiating — let her come to you and use W's delayed stun to punish the dash-chain once she's fully committed. Look to roam when she's forced to shove or reset, since her kit offers little to punish you leaving lane compared to what she gains staying.","late":"Once you have core damage, your combo threatens to kill her back in the trades she used to win for free, and W's zone control becomes a real deterrent against her dash-ins rather than something she just dashes through. Play around vision heavily still — she can flank fast, so ward and track her before grouping. In teamfights, look to flank onto her carries first since Naafiri's own damage focuses squishies just like yours does, and whoever lands the first clean combo usually wins that exchange.","whys":["Level 1: her early stats and pack presence already outclass your rank-1 kit in a straight trade.","Level 2: her second point compounds the pressure while your kit is still passive by design.","Level 3: she gets a full dash-chain combo online well before your W punish is fast enough to matter.","Levels 4-5: continued dash pressure keeps outpacing your still-developing combo threat.","Level 6: Chronobreak's rewind and burst finally give you a real answer to her all-in pattern.","First item: your damage starts threatening to punish her commitment instead of just surviving it.","2+ items: your zone control and flank options let you dictate fights instead of getting run down."]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"neeko","win":["Skill","Skill","Neeko","Skill","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Neeko's root-into-burst combo and disguise trickery punish any careless approach, keeping this stretch in her favor."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Chronobreak gives you the sustain and reposition to survive her group all-in and turn a bad engage into a kill on her instead."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Your combo burst starts to threaten her squishy frame the moment she over-extends her root range."},{"when":"Late","text":"Full-item Ekko can flank through her disguise tricks and punish her before she roots your whole team."}],"wants":{"you":["Approach at odd angles, never predictable pathing into root range","Play around wards to spot her disguise tricks before committing","Wait for her root to whiff before all-inning"],"foe":["Land root off a disguised approach or from the fog","Chain root into full combo for a fast burst kill","Use W clones to bait cooldowns and trades"]},"early":"Neeko's biggest early threat is her root — if she lands it, she gets a free full combo on you with almost no counterplay once it connects. Levels 1-2 stay cautious and vary your walk pattern so she can't time an easy root; her disguise passive also means random minions or wards could be her, so play a bit more paranoid than usual. Levels 3-5 remain her lane to press since her burst-on-root combo out-trades your kit before you have combo damage online — bait the root from max range rather than trading blind.","mid":"Level 6 flips this matchup meaningfully: Chronobreak's healing and reposition let you survive a landed root-combo that would otherwise kill you outright, and punish her for over-extending the all-in. Keep playing around wards and vision to catch her disguise plays before they land — a spotted Neeko loses most of her power. Once her root is on cooldown or she's committed it on a decoy/minion, that's your window to all-in with Q-E-AA before she can reset the trade.","late":"With full items, your burst combo threatens to delete her squishy HP pool the instant she's caught without her root ready, and your own mobility via E/R lets you dodge or bait her engage rather than eating it clean. In teamfights, respect that she can disguise as a minion or ally to set up a surprise root on your carries — ward key flanks and don't let her sit unnoticed. If you can catch her isolated post-root-whiff, Ekko cleans her up fast; if she lands root first in a group fight, she can chain it into a kill before your combo gets going.","whys":["Level 1: her root threat and disguise trickery already outpace anything your rank-1 kit offers.","Level 2: same dynamic continues — she presses the root-combo threat while you stay passive.","Level 3: W comes online but is too slow to punish her poke-root pattern in real time.","Levels 4-5: her burst-on-root combo still out-trades your still-developing kit.","Level 6: Chronobreak's sustain and reposition let you survive and punish her all-in attempts.","First item: your combo burst starts to threaten her squishy frame once she over-extends.","2+ items: your flank speed and burst let you punish her before her root-combo can go off cleanly."]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"orianna","win":["Ekko","Orianna","Orianna","Skill","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Once Orianna gets her ball rolling with W-E-Q combos and shields, her poke and zone control take over this stretch of lane."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Chronobreak lets you dodge or survive her Shockwave pull-together, denying her cleanest all-in/teamfight tool."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Your combo burst starts to threaten her squishy frame if you can dodge or bait the ball placement first."},{"when":"Late","text":"Full items let you flank around her ball zone and punish her before she can group her Shockwave engage."}],"wants":{"you":["Punish her early before she has full ball combo access","Track ball position at all times, never stand where R can pull you","Flank from angles that avoid her ball zone entirely"],"foe":["Land ball-assisted poke to control the wave and zone you out","Land Shockwave to group-pull your team into a teamfight","Shield-peel her own carries with W while pressuring you"]},"early":"You actually have the edge at level 1 since your early trade with Q/AA is stronger before Orianna's ball combo comes fully online — look to punish her if she over-extends for CS. From level 2 onward though, her ball-assisted poke (W-E-Q) and shield start controlling the wave, and this becomes her lane to press through levels 3-5. Play around her ball placement: if it's parked near you, expect a poke combo, so reposition rather than standing still. Her range and shield uptime make prolonged trades a loss once her combo is online.","mid":"Level 6 matters enormously here because Shockwave is one of the best pick/teamfight tools in the game, and getting caught in it with your team is a common way to lose the game outright. Chronobreak gives you a way to dodge the pull with clever positioning or survive it and burst her down for over-extending. Keep tracking her ball position on the minimap — a ball parked away from her means she can't threaten Shockwave range as easily. Look for windows when her ball is out of position to punish her directly.","late":"With full items, your flank speed lets you approach from angles where her ball zone can't set up an easy Shockwave, and your burst combo threatens to kill her fast if you close the gap before she pulls. In teamfights, Orianna wants to group her ball with allies for a game-winning pull, so your job is to either flank and kill her first or bait the Shockwave onto a decoy. A well-timed R from you can also let you survive an unlucky pull and burst her back before her team capitalizes.","whys":["Level 1: your early trade tools slightly out-damage her before her ball combo is fully leveled.","Level 2: her ball gains a second component, letting her start controlling the wave through poke.","Level 3: her full W-E-Q poke combo comes online and out-trades your still-developing kit.","Levels 4-5: continued ball-assisted pressure keeps the lane in her favor as she out-ranges you.","Level 6: Chronobreak gives you a real answer to her Shockwave engage, evening the stakes.","First item: your burst starts threatening her squishy frame whenever you can dodge her ball placement.","2+ items: your flank mobility lets you deny her Shockwave setup and punish her directly."]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"pantheon","win":["Skill","Skill","Skill","Skill","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Pantheon's Comet Spear poke and Shield Vault stun let him all-in you repeatedly through this entire stretch with little risk."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Grand Skyfall pressure on side lanes forces you to play safe, but Chronobreak at least gives you an answer if he dives you directly."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Your combo burst finally threatens to punish him if he over-commits the stun-spear combo without support behind it."},{"when":"Late","text":"Full items let your flank speed and burst outpace his early-game-focused kit, since he falls off relative to a scaling assassin."}],"wants":{"you":["Play behind minions, avoid his Spear/Vault stun range","Ask for early jungle attention to offset his lane dominance","Wait out his early power spike into your own item timings"],"foe":["Poke and all-in relentlessly before level 6 while ahead in raw stats","Use Shield Vault stun to guarantee follow-up damage","Global R pressure to snowball other lanes once ahead"]},"early":"Pantheon is built to dominate exactly this early stretch — his Comet Spear has long range and heavy poke, and Shield Vault stuns you into a full combo with very little counterplay at levels 1-2. Play maximally passive, staying behind minions and avoiding his spear angle entirely; any hit sets up a stun-into-kill sequence. Levels 3-5 don't improve much for you since his stun-combo damage still out-trades your slower-scaling kit — your job here is purely to survive and not feed his snowball, not to contest CS aggressively.","mid":"Level 6 gives Pantheon global pressure via Grand Skyfall, meaning even when he's not in lane he can threaten your team's side lanes or set up jungle plays — ward accordingly and communicate his ult status. Your own level 6 at least gives you Chronobreak as an answer if he dives in for a kill, letting you survive the stun-combo and punish the follow-up. Continue playing for scaling rather than contesting him directly; look for roam windows once he's forced to shove or back.","late":"Pantheon's kit is heavily front-loaded, so once you have your first full item his stun-combo threat starts to fall off relative to your scaling burst and mobility — this is the point where you can start looking for all-in windows instead of just surviving. With full items, your flank speed and combo damage outpace what a mid-game Pantheon can answer, especially since he lacks a true escape once you're on top of him. In teamfights, bait his engage or wait for his stun to whiff before committing, since Ekko punishes an over-extended Pantheon hard in the late game.","whys":["Level 1: his long-range poke and stun setup already outclass anything your rank-1 kit offers.","Level 2: continued spear poke keeps him ahead while your kit stays purely defensive.","Level 3: his stun-into-combo threat scales up further, still out-trading your developing W.","Levels 4-5: his early-game kit remains the stronger threat as you wait out the spike.","Level 6: his global ultimate adds map-wide pressure, though your own R at least offers survival.","First item: your combo starts threatening him back as his early-game kit begins to plateau.","2+ items: your scaling burst and mobility now outpace his front-loaded, falling-off kit."]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"qiyana","win":["Qiyana","Qiyana","Qiyana","Qiyana","Qiyana","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Qiyana unlocks her elemental rune combos and can chain Q-E-W off any wall or bush for a near-unavoidable stun into full combo; your W barrier gets chunked through before you can even react."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Her R extends dash/stun range and lets her reset all-ins mid-fight, while your R is mainly a setup/escape tool until you've banked practice landing parallel convergence on her mobility."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Once you finish Zhonya's or a Seeker's Armguard, Qiyana's dive loses its guaranteed follow-up, and your Z-Drive Resonance procs start punishing her for standing near you."},{"when":"Late","text":"Ekko scales into a pick-and-teamfight monster with Stopwatch-timed R resets and AoE stuns, while Qiyana's damage falls off against tankier frontlines she can no longer one-shot."}],"wants":{"you":["Farm safely with E poke and avoid standing near walls/bushes she can combo off","Hold W barrier for her all-in windows instead of trading poke for poke","Survive to your 2-item spike where teamfight R outclasses her pick potential"],"foe":["Force short trades near terrain to land free Q-E-W stuns","All-in the instant your W or E is on cooldown","Snowball early kills into roams before Ekko comes online"]},"early":"Levels 1-2 are close pokes with E, but from level 3 on Qiyana's elemental combos (especially near any wall) let her all-in you for free — she gets a guaranteed stun into full burst that you can't trade back through with only Q and E up, so you're forced to play passively around terrain and ward for ganks that turn her lead into a snowball.","mid":"Level 6 is a coinflip: her R lets her extend stuns and reset fights, but your ult finally gives you an escape and a delayed burst window, so if you dodge her all-in once you can start punishing her cooldowns with your own combo.","late":"Once you hit your first defensive item her all-in loses its kill threat, and by two items your R becomes a teamfight-swinging AoE stun/burst tool that outscales her falling assassin damage against a scaling team comp.","whys":["Qiyana's elemental combo overload near terrain makes her win level 1-2 trades outright.","Her wall-assisted stun combo snowballs into level 3 as more elemental options unlock.","The terrain all-in threat stays dominant through level 4 before your kit comes online.","Same story into level 5: she can force a stun-into-kill any time you're near a wall.","She keeps the edge into level 6 since her ultimate extends her combo further than your kit can punish yet.","Ekko's Zhonya's/first item timing lets you survive her burst and start punishing her cooldowns instead.","By the 2+ item mark your AoE R and Z-Drive Resonance poke outscale her falling assassin damage in extended fights."]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"ryze","win":["Skill","Skill","Skill","Ekko","Ekko","Ryze","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Ryze is mana-starved and clunky before he strings E-Q-W-Q combos reliably, so trades before level 4 come down to who lands skillshots and Q/E cooldown discipline rather than a clear kit edge."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Ryze's R lets him flash-less roam or reposition to snowball sidelanes and dodge your all-in, giving him a real tempo spike that briefly offsets your own Level 4-5 burst window."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Once you have Sheen/Lich Bane your Q-AA-W trade damage spikes hard and your E poke chunks his low base HP before he stacks enough mana items to spam Q freely."},{"when":"Late","text":"Ekko's burst and reset potential from R lets you delete Ryze in one rotation before his Realm Warp teamfight ult matters, provided you engage before he roots you from range."}],"wants":{"you":["Play safe under turret levels 1-3 and farm with E, avoid extended trades","Snowball your level 4 burst spike into an all-in the moment he's mana-low","Buy an early control ward/Zhonya's item to punish his 6th-level roam timer"],"foe":["Poke with Q and farm safely until mana items let him spam abilities","Use R at 6 to roam or reposition rather than fight you directly","Kite and root with E-Q chains in extended late-game skirmishes"]},"early":"Levels 1-3 are close skill matchups — Ryze is mana-constrained and his combo is slow to string together, so whoever lands more skillshots and punishes cooldowns wins the trade, with no clear kit-level advantage either way.","mid":"Your level 4-5 item and level spike (Sheen procs plus E poke) lets you punish him hard in this window, but his level 6 Realm Warp gives him a roam/reposition tool that can offset your all-in by letting him dodge or redirect the fight entirely.","late":"With your first completed item your burst trades outclass his mana-hungry poke, and by two-plus items your R-enabled burst and reset combo kill him before his ultimate becomes a meaningful teamfight factor.","whys":["Both champions are skill-and-cooldown dependent at level 1 with no kit advantage either way.","Same even footing continues at level 2 as Ryze is still mana-light and slow to combo.","Level 3 remains a skillshot-and-farm contest before either champion's spike kicks in.","Your Sheen-enabled burst window at levels 4-5 gives you the clear damage edge in trades.","That item-and-level spike carries you through level 5 as the favoured side in any skirmish.","Ryze's Realm Warp at level 6 lets him roam or dodge your all-in, briefly swinging tempo back to him.","Ekko's burst/reset combo from R (1st item onward) kills him before his ult matters in a straight fight."]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"swain","win":["Skill","Skill","Swain","Swain","Ekko","Swain","Swain"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Swain's E root plus W drain lane sustain lets him win prolonged trades once he hits level 3, chunking you with unavoidable poke you can't sustain through without your own item spike."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Ekko's level 6 R gives a burst-and-escape window that briefly interrupts his dominance, letting you punish him if you dodge the E root and land your own combo before he ults."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Swain's R (Demonic Ascension) is a zone-control ultimate that heals him and shreds anyone caught in it, and with his first item his sustain and DPS in extended fights climbs even further out of your reach."},{"when":"Late","text":"Late-game Swain becomes a self-sustaining teamfight nightmare — his R zone plus passive healing outlasts your burst unless you can one-shot him before he presses R, which gets harder as he stacks more HP/AP."}],"wants":{"you":["Avoid extended trades once he hits level 3 and his E-W combo starts chunking you","Look for short trades punishing his root cooldown, then reset with W barrier","Save your level 6 burst window to punish him before he can safely use his own R"],"foe":["Land E roots to lock you into extended drain trades with W sustain","Farm safely under the safety of his ranged poke and lane sustain","Use R to zone and out-sustain all-in attempts in both lane and teamfights"]},"early":"Levels 1-2 are close as neither champion has their core tools online, but the moment Swain hits level 3 his E root into W drain trade starts winning extended fights outright, forcing you to play short trades and avoid getting locked into sustained damage exchanges.","mid":"Your level 6 R gives you a burst-and-mobility window to punish him if you can dodge his root, but this is a brief equalizer — his kit's sustain and zone control keep him ahead in raw lane dominance through this stretch.","late":"By his first item Swain's healing and DPS scale further out of reach, and by two-plus items his R becomes a self-sustaining teamfight zone that outlasts your burst unless you can delete him before he presses it, making this matchup increasingly rough as the game goes on.","whys":["Neither champion has a spike online at level 1, so it's an even skill matchup.","Still even at level 2 before Swain's root-and-drain combo comes online.","Swain's E-W chain trade wins outright once it unlocks at level 3.","That sustain-and-root advantage continues through levels 4-5 as he outscales your poke.","Ekko's R grants a burst-and-escape window at level 6 that lets you punish him if you dodge his root.","Swain's healing and DPS scale further ahead with his first item, reclaiming the advantage.","His R zone-control ultimate makes him a self-sustaining teamfight threat that outlasts you late."]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"sylas","win":["Sylas","Sylas","Sylas","Skill","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Sylas's Q-E-Q combo with W sustain lets him all-in you the moment he has both Q charges and W stacks, out-trading your E poke thanks to his built-in lifesteal and repeated Q hits."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"His ultimate steals whatever enemy ult was last cast nearby, so if he's near your teammates when you fight he can turn your own kit's tools into his all-in tool — but if he can't steal your R specifically it's an even fight."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Once you finish your first item your burst and Z-Drive Resonance procs let you punish his cooldowns, and Sylas's all-in loses steam without a fed lead since his damage is front-loaded and mana-hungry early."},{"when":"Late","text":"Ekko's reset-and-burst kit from R plus item power spikes ahead of Sylas's scaling in the late game, letting you delete him in a rotation before his stolen ult (if any) matters."}],"wants":{"you":["Play passively under turret through level 3-5 and avoid extended trades","Bait his Q-E all-in before your item spike, then punish the cooldown","Look to snowball once you finish your first item and his early lead fades"],"foe":["All-in with Q-E-Q and W sustain the moment both Q charges are up","Steal a nearby ultimate at 6 to add burst or utility to his combo","Snowball an early kill into a lead before Ekko's items come online"]},"early":"From level 3 Sylas can chain his double-Q combo with E's stun and W lifesteal to win any extended trade, and since his damage and sustain are both front-loaded you're forced to play passively and avoid all-in windows until your own kit and items catch up.","mid":"Level 6 is roughly even — his ultimate can steal a nearby enemy ult for extra utility or burst, but unless he's stealing your own R specifically it doesn't swing the fight decisively either way, so cooldown management matters more than raw power here.","late":"Your first item turns the tide hard: Z-Drive Resonance procs and burst combos let you punish his all-in attempts, and by two-plus items your reset-capable R outscales his front-loaded damage, letting you win fights he can no longer force cleanly.","whys":["Sylas's Q-E-Q combo with W sustain wins level 1 trades before your kit is online.","Same all-in advantage holds at level 2 as his double-Q combo out-damages your poke.","He remains ahead through level 3 with stacked Q charges and lifesteal sustain.","Level 6 nets out even since his ult-steal is only a real swing if it grabs something game-changing.","Ekko's first item lets your burst and resonance procs start punishing his cooldowns.","That item-power edge continues through the extended mid-game trades.","Ekko's reset-capable R and scaling burst outclass his front-loaded kit in the late game."]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"syndra","win":["Skill","Skill","Syndra","Syndra","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Syndra's Q-W-E stun combo one-shots squishies from level 3 onward with enough spheres stacked, and her range advantage lets her poke you down safely before you can close the gap with E."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Her R adds three more spheres for a near-guaranteed kill combo on cooldown-locked targets, but your own level 6 R gives you a delayed burst-and-mobility answer if you dodge her stun setup."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Once you have Sheen your all-in trades close the damage gap fast, and by completing a second item your Z-Drive Resonance and burst rotation start outscaling her sphere-stun combo in skirmishes."},{"when":"Late","text":"Ekko's reset potential from R and burst item spikes let you delete her in one rotation if you can close the gap, since she has no reliable escape once you're on top of her."}],"wants":{"you":["Play under turret and avoid her max-range Q poke until you have gap-closing tools","Watch her sphere count and dodge the stun window rather than trading into it","Snowball off your item spikes to close the range gap and punish her lack of escape"],"foe":["Poke safely with Q from max range and stack spheres for a stun combo","Land the E stun off cooldown-locked or immobile targets for a full burst kill","Zone with sphere placement to deny farm and force you out of range"]},"early":"Levels 1-2 are close skill matchups as neither ultimate or full combo is online yet, but from level 3 Syndra's Q-W-E stun-and-burst combo starts one-shotting you from safe range if you get caught by even one sphere, so you're forced to play passively and dodge her stun setups rather than trade back.","mid":"Her level 6 R adds extra spheres for an even more reliable kill combo, but your own R at 6 gives you a delayed burst window and mobility to close the gap if you can dodge her stun — the fight becomes about who lands their combo first.","late":"With your first item your all-in trades close the damage gap significantly, and by two-plus items your reset-capable R and burst rotation outscale her sphere-stun combo, letting you delete her once you're in melee range since she has no escape.","whys":["Neither champion's full combo threatens yet at level 1, so it's an even skill matchup.","Same even footing at level 2 before either ultimate or key items come online.","Syndra's stacked-sphere stun combo starts one-shotting you outright from level 3.","That ranged burst-and-stun advantage continues through levels 4-5 as she zones freely.","Her R adds extra spheres for an even more reliable kill combo at level 6.","Ekko's first item closes the damage gap fast, letting your all-in trades even out.","By two-plus items your reset-capable R and burst outscale her combo once you close the gap."]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"taliyah","win":["Skill","Skill","Skill","Skill","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Taliyah's Q-W combo and wall-jump mobility make her a slippery poke threat early, but neither of you has a decisive all-in yet, so trades stay close and come down to skillshot accuracy and wave control."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Your R comes online first in real fighting power — Taliyah's R is a roam/teamfight tool with limited direct dueling value, so level 6 tips the lane matchup in your favor if she can't disengage in time."},{"when":"1st item","text":"With Sheen procs and Z-Drive Resonance, your all-in damage output jumps sharply, while Taliyah's kit remains built around poke-and-reposition rather than sustained trading power."},{"when":"Late","text":"Ekko's burst-and-reset R lets you punish her lack of an escape if you close distance, and since her damage scales more toward waveclear and roams than lane duels, you consistently win skirmishes late."}],"wants":{"you":["Trade evenly with E poke and avoid overextending into her wall-assisted mobility","Play patiently until your level 6/item spikes give you a clear all-in advantage","Punish her when she's used Q/W to clear waves or roam, leaving her exposed"],"foe":["Poke safely with Q and reposition using W-created walls to avoid trades","Roam mid-game using R's global move speed to snowball sidelanes","Avoid direct all-ins against Ekko once he hits his level 6/item spikes"]},"early":"Levels 1-5 are a close skillshot-and-wave-management contest — Taliyah's Q-W combo and wall mobility let her poke and reposition safely, but neither of you has a clear all-in advantage yet, so trades stay even and the lane is decided more by roams and jungle pathing than raw kit power.","mid":"Your level 6 R is the first real dueling spike in this matchup since her ultimate is built for roaming and teamfight repositioning rather than lane all-ins, so from 6 onward you can start forcing fights she has to respect.","late":"By your first item your burst output climbs sharply and by two-plus items your reset-capable R punishes her lack of an escape tool, letting you consistently win skirmishes since her kit scales toward waveclear and utility rather than raw trading power.","whys":["Both champions are limited to skillshot poke at level 1 with no clear kit advantage.","Same even trade dynamic at level 2 as neither all-in threat is online yet.","Taliyah's wall-mobility keeps trades close through level 3 without tipping decisively.","Levels 4-5 stay even as both champions rely on poke and positioning rather than all-ins.","Ekko's R gives the first real dueling power spike at level 6, tipping the lane your way.","Your first item's burst and resonance procs let you punish her lack of sustained damage.","By two-plus items your reset-capable R consistently wins skirmishes against her utility kit."]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"talon","win":["Skill","Talon","Talon","Talon","Talon","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Talon's W-Q-E combo lets him leap in, cut, and vault away with near-zero counterplay once he hits level 2-3, punishing your lack of a reliable escape before you have Sheen or your ult online."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"His R grants stealth and mobility for a repeatable dive-and-reset pattern that keeps him ahead in lane dominance, since your own kit still lacks a hard answer to his burst-and-vault combo at this stage."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Once you finish your first item your Z-Drive Resonance and Sheen procs let you punish his all-in attempts, and your R finally gives you a burst-and-escape tool that matches his mobility."},{"when":"Late","text":"Ekko's reset-capable R and scaling burst let you win skirmishes late since Talon's damage is front-loaded and he struggles to burst through your barrier and defensive itemization in extended fights."}],"wants":{"you":["Play under turret and avoid roaming lanes he can flank until you have an escape","Hold W barrier for his all-in and punish the vault cooldown after he commits","Snowball your item spike and look to punish his overextensions post-6"],"foe":["All-in with W-Q-E vault combo the moment you're out of position or overextended","Use R stealth to roam and pick off squishies in side lanes with impunity","Snowball an early kill into a lead before Ekko's items and R come online"]},"early":"Level 1 is close, but from level 2 Talon's W-Q-E combo lets him engage, burst, and vault away safely, and since you lack a reliable gap-closer or escape this early he can freely punish any misstep with almost no counterplay, forcing you into a passive farming pattern under turret.","mid":"His level 6 R adds stealth and repeatable dive potential that keeps him dominant through this stretch, since your own kit still doesn't have a hard answer to his burst-and-vault pattern until your first item and ult are both online.","late":"Once you complete your first item your resonance procs and burst finally let you punish his all-ins, and by two-plus items your reset-capable R gives you the mobility and burst to outduel him, since his damage is front-loaded and falls off against your scaling and defensive options.","whys":["Level 1 is an even skill matchup before either champion's combo threatens fully.","Talon's W-Q-E vault combo starts punishing you hard from level 2 onward.","That same burst-and-escape advantage continues at level 3 with no real counterplay from you.","Levels 4-5 remain his window as you still lack a gap-closer or hard engage answer.","His R adds stealth and dive potential at level 6, extending his lane dominance further.","Ekko's first item lets your resonance procs and burst finally punish his overextensions.","By two-plus items your reset-capable R gives you the tools to outduel his front-loaded kit."]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"twistedfate","win":["Skill","Skill","Skill","Skill","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"TF's Wild Cards poke and Pick A Card stun windows make short trades risky; Ekko should farm with Timewinder and avoid standing still for the blue-card stun."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"TF's Destiny gives him global pressure and a snowball tool, so Ekko has to respect the reveal before overextending on either side of the map."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Ekko's burst combo (E-slow, Q, W-stun, R) starts one-shotting squishies around Lich Bane/first burst item, well before TF's damage catches up."},{"when":"Late","text":"Ekko's Chronobreak reset and burst combo massively outscale TF's Wild Cards poke in teamfights and pick potential."}],"wants":{"you":["Farm safely under blue-card threat, don't facecheck brush","Punish TF whenever Pick A Card is down, all-in with Q-AA-W","Look for kill windows the moment you hit a burst item"],"foe":["Poke with Wild Cards and land blue-card stuns for picks","Use Destiny to set up global plays and Gold Card ganks","Snowball off level 6 picks before Ekko's items come online"]},"early":"Levels 1-2 are close to even but slightly nervy for Ekko — TF's Wild Cards chip away at HP without much retaliation risk, and a landed blue card into follow-up can end the lane fast, so Ekko should hover near minions rather than brush edges. By level 3-5 TF's card variance (blue-card stuns, gold-card global ganks once he hits 6) keeps Ekko playing reactively, farming through poke with Timewinder rather than forcing all-ins into an unrevealed card.","mid":"At level 6 TF's Destiny turns the map into his playground — he can reveal Ekko for a jungler gank or snipe a low-health target across the map, so Ekko needs to track his ult timer and avoid getting caught overextended. Ekko's own kit is still solid here (Parallel Convergence zone control, Phase Dive engage) but TF's global threat and stun-card picks mean this phase leans slightly toward the card shark until Ekko's items catch up.","late":"Once Ekko finishes his first burst item (usually Lich Bane or a burst rush), his combo one-shots squishies and Chronobreak lets him dive fights safely with a free reset if he drops low — this is where the matchup flips hard. Late game Ekko's teamfight burst and repositioning via ult outclass TF's card poke and single-target picks, making him the far scarier threat in 5v5s and pick attempts alike.","whys":["Level 1 is a coinflip skill matchup, neither champion has a decisive early trading tool yet","Level 2 stays even for the same reason, both are still using basic combos without stun-card reveals landing consistently","Level 3-5 hinges on TF landing his blue-card stun or Ekko dodging it, so it's a skill-expression window not a hard favor","Levels 4-5 remain skill-based as trades are short and punishable both ways depending on card reads","Level 6 favors Ekko because his all-in combo and zone control from Parallel Convergence starts outpacing TF's single-target Destiny snipe in a straight duel","First item favors Ekko since his burst combo (Q-W-R chain) begins one-shotting squishy TF before his damage item ramps up","2+ items favors Ekko decisively — Chronobreak resets and full burst combo dominate TF's poke-and-pick kit in extended fights"]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"veigar","win":["Ekko","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Ekko's mobility via E dash and Q slow lets him dodge Veigar's Dark Matter and Baleful Strike stacks while punishing his lack of escape with all-in trades."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Veigar's Event Horizon cage is scary for a pick, but Ekko's Phase Dive and Chronobreak give him tools to disengage or bait the cage without getting fully punished."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Ekko snowballs first item burst combos into a stationary, low-mobility Veigar who has almost no way to escape the W-stun into R sequence."},{"when":"Late","text":"Ekko's mobility, resets, and burst combo continue to run down a target-dummy-mobility Veigar even as his AP scaling gets scary, because Ekko simply denies him the setup window."}],"wants":{"you":["Dodge skillshots with E dash timing, punish missed Baleful Strikes","All-in whenever Event Horizon and Dark Matter are on cooldown","Snowball roams off lane dominance since Veigar can't threaten you back"],"foe":["Stack Baleful Strike passive for burst damage on low-mobility targets","Land Event Horizon cage into full combo for a kill","Scale AP items into one-shot potential in teamfights"]},"early":"From level 1, Ekko's dash and slow let him weave in and out of Veigar's Baleful Strike range while Veigar has almost nothing to punish a well-timed E with — this is Ekko's lane to control from minute one. Through levels 3-5 Ekko keeps abusing his mobility advantage, poking with Timewinder and diving in for trades whenever Veigar's skillshots miss, since a rooted-in-place mage has no answer to a dive he can't escape.","mid":"Level 6 gives Veigar Event Horizon, a genuine kill threat if he catches Ekko standing still in the cage, but Ekko's own kit (Parallel Convergence zone, Phase Dive re-engage, and Chronobreak as a get-out-of-jail card) means he can play around the cage far more safely than Veigar can play around Ekko's dive. This phase stays clearly in Ekko's favor because his mobility answers Veigar's one big pick tool.","late":"Once Ekko has his first burst item, he simply runs down Veigar in skirmishes — Veigar has no dash, no blink, nothing to escape a slow-into-stun-into-burst sequence, and Ekko's damage output rivals or exceeds Veigar's own scaling. Late game, even as Veigar's AP numbers get scary on paper, Ekko's mobility lets him pick his fights and avoid ever standing in Veigar's kill zone, keeping this matchup lopsided in Ekko's favor throughout.","whys":["Level 1 favors Ekko because his dash and slow already outclass Veigar's skillshot-only kit at point-blank range","Level 2 stays Ekko-favored as Baleful Strike stacking requires hits Ekko can dodge with E","Level 3-5 favors Ekko since his mobility lets him punish any missed cage or Dark Matter attempt","Levels 4-5 remain Ekko-favored for the same reason — Veigar simply cannot threaten a target that can dash away","Level 6 favors Ekko because his own disengage and re-engage tools neutralize the threat of Event Horizon","First item favors Ekko as his burst combo runs down an escape-less Veigar before Veigar can land his full combo","2+ items favors Ekko because his mobility continues to deny Veigar's setup windows even as both scale"]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"vex","win":["Skill","Skill","Skill","Skill","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Vex's Mistral Bolt and Personal Space punish approach angles, so Ekko has to time his E dash to close distance without eating a full poke rotation first."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Vex's Shadow Surge fear is a strong pick tool if she catches Ekko out, but her lack of true mobility means Ekko can often bait it and dash away before the follow-up lands."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Ekko's burst combo starts running down Vex once he has a lead — she has no dash, only a dash-punish passive, which stops mattering once Ekko is diving with Phase Dive."},{"when":"Late","text":"Ekko's mobility and reset via Chronobreak let him repeatedly dive backline Vex in teamfights, where her immobility becomes a glaring weakness against his all-in kit."}],"wants":{"you":["Farm through Mistral Bolt poke, avoid dashing into Personal Space punish","Time E dash for engages when her fear (Shadow Surge) is down","Snowball into dives once ahead — she can't disengage"],"foe":["Poke safely with Mistral Bolt and passive gloom stacks","Punish any dash-heavy engage with the Personal Space damage bonus","Land Shadow Surge fear into full combo for a pick"]},"early":"Levels 1-2 lean skill-based — Vex's Mistral Bolt poke stings but Ekko can farm through it with Timewinder without taking bonus damage, so it's mostly about who lands more pokes cleanly. Through levels 3-5, Vex's Personal Space passive punishes any dash into her, meaning Ekko has to be smart about when he commits E rather than using it purely to close distance, keeping this stretch even rather than a clear favor either way.","mid":"Level 6 is where Ekko starts to pull ahead: Vex's Shadow Surge fear is scary if it connects, but she has zero true mobility to disengage or reposition, so Ekko can often bait the fear from range and then dash in once it's spent. Ekko's own combo threatens more consistent damage in this window, and his Phase Dive reset lets him capitalize on any misstep from a Vex who has committed her only escape-adjacent tool.","late":"Once Ekko has his first burst item, he can reliably run Vex down — her total lack of a dash or blink means Phase Dive engages land almost freely, and Ekko's combo output starts outpacing her poke-based damage profile. Late game this gap widens further: Chronobreak lets Ekko dive Vex repeatedly in teamfights without fear of retaliation, since she simply cannot punish or escape his mobility advantage the way a dash-having mage could.","whys":["Level 1 is an even skill matchup, both sides trade pokes without a clear structural advantage yet","Level 2 remains skill-based since Mistral Bolt poke and Ekko's farm pattern roughly cancel out","Level 3-5 stays a skill window because Personal Space punishes careless dashes, keeping Ekko's engages measured","Levels 4-5 hold at skill-based for the same passive-punish reason, trades are still close","Level 6 favors Ekko since Vex's immobility lets him bait Shadow Surge and dive once it's used","First item favors Ekko because his burst combo runs down an escape-less Vex before her damage output catches up","2+ items favors Ekko decisively as his repeated dive-and-reset pattern exploits Vex's complete lack of mobility"]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"viktor","win":["Skill","Skill","Viktor","Viktor","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Viktor's Gravity Field zone control ramps up hard once he gets his augment upgrades, forcing Ekko to farm from range rather than diving into the siege zone."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Viktor's Chaos Storm ultimate adds huge zone damage and can end a fight Ekko commits into carelessly, so Ekko must wait for it to be down before all-inning."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Ekko's burst combo starts one-shotting Viktor once Ekko has a lead, since Viktor has no hard escape besides Gravity Field's slow-zone repositioning."},{"when":"Late","text":"Ekko's mobility and reset via Chronobreak let him flank and burst Viktor down before his own damage output or Death Ray zoning can punish the dive."}],"wants":{"you":["Farm safely outside Gravity Field range, avoid E-dashing into the zone","Bait Chaos Storm before committing to an all-in","Snowball roams and burst once you have first-item damage"],"foe":["Zone with Gravity Field and Death Ray to control the wave","Land Chaos Storm on top of Ekko for a huge damage swing","Scale into a hexcore-augmented late game with strong AoE zoning"]},"early":"Levels 1-2 are close, with both champions relying on basic poke and farm patterns without a clear structural edge. By level 3-5, Viktor's augmented kit — especially Gravity Field zoning and Death Ray poke — starts to punish Ekko for standing in the wave or diving carelessly, giving Viktor the edge in a phase where his siege potential outpaces Ekko's early trading tools.","mid":"Level 6 tips further toward Viktor: Chaos Storm adds a huge AoE damage-over-time zone that can shred Ekko if he commits an all-in without tracking the cooldown, making this one of the scarier windows in the matchup. Ekko has to play patiently here, using Timewinder to poke from outside Gravity Field range and waiting for Viktor's cooldowns before looking for anything aggressive.","late":"Once Ekko lands his first burst item, the matchup flips — his combo (E-slow, Q, W-stun, R) threatens to one-shot Viktor, who has no dash or blink to escape a well-timed dive, so Ekko can punish any overextension hard. Late game, Ekko's mobility and Chronobreak reset let him flank around Viktor's frontal zone control entirely, picking him off in skirmishes before Death Ray or Chaos Storm ever get to punish the engage.","whys":["Level 1 is an even skill matchup, neither side has a decisive early edge in poke or trades","Level 2 stays skill-based as both are still farming with basic combos before key augment power spikes","Level 3-5 favors Viktor because his zone control from Gravity Field and Death Ray outpaces Ekko's short-range trading tools","Levels 4-5 remain Viktor-favored for the same reason, his siege potential punishes any careless engage","Level 6 favors Viktor since Chaos Storm's AoE damage zone punishes an ill-timed Ekko all-in severely","First item favors Ekko because his burst combo threatens a one-shot on an escape-less Viktor","2+ items favors Ekko as his mobility lets him flank around Viktor's zone control and burst him down in skirmishes"]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"vladimir","win":["Ekko","Skill","Skill","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Vladimir's Sanguine Pool makes him untouchable during dashes, so Ekko has to bait the pool before committing his E rather than diving straight through it."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Vlad's Hemoplague adds a big AoE damage amp, dangerous in extended fights, but its long cooldown means Ekko can often engage before it's back up."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Ekko's burst combo starts overwhelming Vladimir's sustain, since his healing can't keep pace with a full Q-W-R burst sequence landing back to back."},{"when":"Late","text":"Ekko's mobility and reset via Chronobreak let him repeatedly re-engage Vladimir, whose own mobility (Sanguine Pool) is purely defensive and eventually gets baited out."}],"wants":{"you":["Bait Sanguine Pool before committing your dash and stun","Punish Vladimir hard early since his sustain and pool aren't online at rank 1","All-in once you have a burst-item lead, before Hemoplague resets"],"foe":["Use Sanguine Pool to dodge skillshots and stuns, then punish the whiff","Stack Crimson Pact bonus health and sustain through poke damage","Land Hemoplague on top of Ekko before a big all-in for the damage amp"]},"early":"Level 1 favors Ekko outright — Vladimir doesn't have Sanguine Pool until level 2, so his very first level is his weakest, and Ekko can punish him hard with Timewinder poke and an early E-Q trade before the pool comes online. Levels 2-5 settle into a more even skill window once Vlad has his pool to dodge Ekko's stun, making trades a matter of baiting the pool correctly rather than a clean favor either way.","mid":"By levels 4-5 and into level 6, Ekko pulls back ahead: his zone control from Parallel Convergence and burst combo threaten more than Vlad's poke-and-sustain game can answer, and while Hemoplague is a real threat in extended skirmishes, its long cooldown means Ekko frequently gets to force fights while it's down. This phase favors Ekko's proactive playstyle over Vlad's more passive scaling pattern.","late":"Once Ekko has his first burst item, his combo simply outpaces what Vladimir's sustain can heal through — Vlad has no way to escape a well-baited stun into full burst, and his healing curve can't keep up with burst damage the way it can with sustained poke. Late game, Ekko's mobility and Chronobreak reset let him keep forcing skirmishes on his terms, baiting out Sanguine Pool and then diving in once it's spent, keeping this matchup in Ekko's favor throughout.","whys":["Level 1 favors Ekko because Vladimir doesn't unlock Sanguine Pool until level 2, leaving him with no dodge tool","Level 2 is an even skill window as Vlad's pool comes online and both sides adjust their trade patterns","Level 3-5 stays skill-based since trades hinge on whether Ekko can bait the pool before committing his stun","Levels 4-5 favor Ekko as his zone control and burst combo start to outpace Vlad's poke-and-sustain scaling","Level 6 favors Ekko because Hemoplague's long cooldown often leaves Vlad without his damage amp when fights start","First item favors Ekko since his burst sequence outpaces what Vladimir's sustain can heal through","2+ items favors Ekko as he can keep forcing favorable skirmishes by baiting Sanguine Pool and diving after"]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"xerath","win":["Skill","Skill","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Xerath's long-range Arcanopulse poke hurts, but Ekko's E dash closes the gap fast enough to punish him once he's used his ranged tools on the wave."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Xerath's Rite of the Arcane global ultimate threatens picks across the map, but its long cast time means Ekko can usually walk out or use his own mobility to dodge."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Ekko's burst combo starts closing distance and one-shotting a squishy, low-mobility Xerath before his poke damage can offset the dive."},{"when":"Late","text":"Ekko's mobility and Chronobreak reset let him repeatedly dive Xerath's backline position, where his total lack of escape becomes fight-losing."}],"wants":{"you":["Farm safely behind minions early, avoid standing in Arcanopulse sightlines","Close the gap with E dash once Xerath commits pokes to the wave","Dive and burst once you have item power, he can't escape"],"foe":["Poke from max range with Arcanopulse and Eye of Destruction stuns","Zone Ekko off the wave using superior range","Snipe picks globally with Rite of the Arcane once ahead"]},"early":"Levels 1-2 favor Xerath's long range — his Arcanopulse poke outranges anything Ekko can answer with early, so Ekko has to play patiently behind minions and avoid unnecessary trades while he's still short on mobility uses. From level 3 onward, though, Ekko's E dash lets him close the gap on Xerath immediately after he's committed a poke to the wave, flipping the trade pattern in Ekko's favor for the rest of the mid-game.","mid":"By levels 4-5 and into level 6, Ekko is clearly ahead — Xerath's kit is entirely built around keeping distance, and once Ekko is in his face there's very little Xerath can do to disengage. His ultimate, Rite of the Arcane, is a real threat globally, but its long cast animation gives Ekko time to react and reposition, so it rarely changes the outcome of the lane phase itself.","late":"Once Ekko has his first burst item, he simply erases Xerath in any 1-on-1 — closing the gap with Phase Dive and landing a full burst combo before Xerath's poke damage can offset it, since Xerath has zero escape tools once engaged. Late game this gap only widens: Chronobreak lets Ekko dive repeatedly into Xerath's backline position in teamfights, where his complete lack of mobility makes him one of the easiest priority targets on the enemy team.","whys":["Level 1 favors Xerath because his long-range poke outclasses anything Ekko can answer with at rank 1","Level 2 stays Xerath-favored for the same reason, his range advantage is still uncontested this early","Level 3-5 favors Ekko once his E dash lets him close distance on Xerath immediately after a poke commitment","Levels 4-5 remain Ekko-favored as his all-in potential clearly outpaces Xerath's lack of escape tools","Level 6 favors Ekko because Xerath's long-cast ultimate rarely lands cleanly enough to offset his lane weakness","First item favors Ekko since his burst combo closes the gap and kills an escape-less Xerath before poke can offset it","2+ items favors Ekko decisively as his dive-and-reset pattern exploits Xerath's total lack of mobility in fights"]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"yasuo","win":["Skill","Skill","Yasuo","Skill","Ekko","Yasuo","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Yasuo's Sweeping Blade and knockup-into-Last-Breath combo punishes Ekko's short-range trades, especially once he has a wind wall to negate Timewinder poke."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Yasuo's Last Breath deals huge burst if he lands a knockup setup, a genuine kill threat Ekko must respect by not overextending into his dash range."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Yasuo's crit-scaling first item lets his knockup-into-Last-Breath combo threaten a near one-shot on Ekko before Ekko's own burst item comes online."},{"when":"Late","text":"With 2+ items Ekko's burst combo and zone control from Parallel Convergence catch up and start to outpace Yasuo's damage window, giving him the edge in extended skirmishes."}],"wants":{"you":["Bait Wind Wall before committing Timewinder poke","Avoid short trades into his dash range, especially near level 6","Snowball with burst item power and zone control once ahead"],"foe":["Wall Ekko's key poke tools with Wind Wall","Land a knockup into Last Breath for a huge burst window","Snowball crit items into a one-shot late-game threat"]},"early":"Levels 1-2 are close, with both champions relying on short trades and neither having a decisive structural edge yet. By levels 3-5, Yasuo's Wind Wall starts to negate Ekko's Timewinder poke, and his Sweeping Blade dash combined with a knockup punishes Ekko for overextending, tipping this specific stretch of the lane toward Yasuo's favor.","mid":"Level 6 is Yasuo's biggest spike — Last Breath off a knockup can delete Ekko in a single combo, so Ekko has to respect this threat by staying outside his dash range and not walking into easy knockup setups near minions or terrain. It's a genuine skill check throughout this window, with Yasuo able to punish any misplay severely, though Ekko's own zone control gives him tools to fight back if he plays it patiently.","late":"Yasuo's first crit item lets his knockup-into-Last-Breath combo threaten to near one-shot Ekko before Ekko's own burst item is finished, making this an early-scaling danger window Ekko has to respect. But once Ekko catches up to 2+ items, his combo and Parallel Convergence zone control start to outpace what Yasuo can answer with, giving Ekko the edge in fully-scaled skirmishes and teamfights.","whys":["Level 1 is an even skill matchup, both champions trade cautiously without a clear early edge","Level 2 stays skill-based for the same reason, short trades are close and punishable both ways","Level 3-5 favors Yasuo because Wind Wall negates Ekko's ranged poke while his dash-knockup combo punishes overextension","Levels 4-5 remain a skill window as both sides adjust trade patterns around Wind Wall timing","Level 6 favors Ekko since his zone control and all-in tools begin to outpace Yasuo's damage in a straight fight at this point","First item favors Yasuo because his crit-scaling knockup combo threatens a near one-shot before Ekko's own burst item is ready","2+ items favors Ekko as his burst combo and zone control catch up and outpace Yasuo's damage window in extended fights"]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"yone","win":["Skill","Skill","Yone","Skill","Ekko","Yone","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Yone unlocks Mortal Steel/Wind combos into E-Q-R stack and can dash through your Timewinder for a trade if you stand still; keep casting Q from angles he can't Q1 through and don't feed him a still target for the Lvl3 all-in."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Yone's Fate Sealed lets him pull you and himself into a follow-up burst with his laner or just execute low-HP wave trades; you don't have a real answer to sudden dive pressure until you have E-W to blink away, so play the wave passively around this level."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Once you finish your first burst item (Lich Bane/Shadowflame) your Q-AA-W-Q-R trade outdamages his sustained AA-Q pattern in a straight fight, and your E gives you the escape/reset he lacks against a fed backline."},{"when":"Late","text":"Late you're a flanking pick-machine with Chronobreak resets while Yone is a mobile split/dive threat vulnerable to CC chains; a clean W stun into R detonation deletes him before his ult can reposition, but if he catches you isolated with Q3 knockup you die fast."}],"wants":{"you":["Farm safe under tower early, avoid standing still for his Q1 stack","Use Parallel Convergence to zone his all-ins after level 3","Roam or group once E is up for the trade-then-reset pattern"],"foe":["Stack Q1 by hitting minions then Q2 dash onto you for free damage","All-in hard at 3 and 6 when you're static or low on E cooldown","Save Fate Sealed to catch multiple targets or execute you post-trade"]},"early":"Levels 1-2 are close to even as both champs poke with skillshots, but by level 3 Yone's Q1-stack into Q2 dash plus E-R combo threatens a real all-in if you're caught standing still, so keep repositioning and don't overextend on CS.","mid":"Level 4-5 stays contestable through Skill trades, but his level 6 spike with Fate Sealed is a genuine kill window that punishes you before your E is off cooldown, so play the wave passive and ward your flanks; once you hit 6 yourself you can trade back with W-Q-R combos, though Yone can still find a big all-in later if he catches a good Q3 knockup.","late":"With your first burst item online you out-trade him in a straight fight and W-R gives you a reliable pick tool with Chronobreak as a safety net, but Yone remains dangerous split-pushing or diving from stealth, so group for objectives and force fights where your team can peel or follow up his engage.","whys":["Level 1 is an even lane phase with both champs just poking, no clear kit advantage yet.","Level 2 stays balanced as cooldowns and combos are still coming online for both sides.","Yone's Q1-stack into Q2/E combo lets him force a favorable all-in once he hits level 3 first.","Level 4-5 returns to an even skill matchup as Ekko's kit starts catching up in trade potential.","Ekko's Parallel Convergence and E reposition give you the edge in level 6 skirmishes once your ultimate and stun are both live.","Yone's Fate Sealed at level 6 threatens a kill window on you before your escape tools are consistently up.","Ekko's Chronobreak reset and burst-item trade damage make you the stronger threat in late-game skirmishes and picks."]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"zed","win":["Skill","Skill","Zed","Zed","Ekko","Zed","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Zed unlocks Living Shadow-swap all-ins once he has Q-W-E maxed enough to combo, and his shadow lets him poke with Razor Shuriken risk-free while dodging your Timewinder; don't let him stack Q harass on the wave without punishing his shadow cooldown."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Death Mark at level 6 is Zed's real kill threat — he can shadow in, mark you, and burst before you can react, especially if you're pushed up or your E is down; play passive around the wave the moment he hits 6 until your own ultimate is live."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Your first item (Lich Bane or Shadowflame) plus Parallel Convergence lets you zone and burst him in return fights, and your E-W combo gives you a reliable dodge for his Death Mark reveal-execute, flipping the trade back in your favor."},{"when":"Late","text":"Late game your Chronobreak reset punishes his all-in the moment he commits Death Mark, since you can W away and detonate for a bigger hit than his mark deals, but if he catches you without E up he still deletes squishies in one rotation."}],"wants":{"you":["Play safe under tower before level 6, don't overextend into shadow harass","Hold Parallel Convergence to punish his shadow swap-ins","Time E-W to dodge Death Mark's reveal and turn the fight"],"foe":["Poke with Q through shadow to avoid retaliation before level 6","All-in immediately off Death Mark before your escape is up","Reset Death Mark's mark on you if the first burst doesn't kill"]},"early":"Levels 1-2 stay close since both champions are trading skillshot poke, but once Zed reaches level 3 his shadow swap-ins with Q-W combos start punishing you for extended trades, and this pressure holds through level 5 while he out-scales your kit in raw lane all-in strength.","mid":"Zed's level 6 Death Mark is the defining threat of the mid-game — a shadow in, mark, and burst before you can react is lethal if you're caught without E up, so respect his all-in range hard the moment he hits 6, and expect him to look for one more big all-in later with Death Mark reset timing once items come online.","late":"Once you finish your first burst item you can trade back hard using E to dodge his mark reveal and Chronobreak to punish the follow-through, making you the safer late-game pick threat in skirmishes, but Zed still one-shots isolated targets if he catches you with your dash down, so group tightly and ward his flanks.","whys":["Level 1 is an even poke phase with neither champion having a decisive kit advantage yet.","Level 2 remains balanced while both sides build toward their level 3-5 power spikes.","Zed's shadow-enabled all-in combo comes online at level 3 and starts winning extended trades.","Zed's kit advantage continues through levels 4-5 as his shadow harass outpaces your poke.","Ekko's Parallel Convergence and item power let you win skirmishes once your ultimate is live at 6.","Zed's Death Mark is a lethal execute threat the instant he hits level 6, favoring him in all-in windows.","Ekko's Chronobreak reset and burst trade damage make you the stronger threat in late-game fights."]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"ziggs","win":["Ekko","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Ziggs has zero mobility and telegraphs every Bouncing Bomb/Satchel Charge arc, so you can hop your E onto him mid-cast and punish with Q-AA-W for a big trade he can't answer without Flash; look to all-in the moment he uses Satchel Charge to zone since it's now down for the wave."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Your Chronobreak lets you dive through his Mega Inferno Bomb zone and reset the fight after he's spent his combo, while his own ult is a slow, telegraphed poke tool with no escape utility, so level 6 all-ins heavily favor you if you commit through his wave-clear range."},{"when":"1st item","text":"With a first item online your dash-in burst kills him before he can kite with W, and any all-in near his own turret or jungle bush is close to free since he has no repositioning tool beyond Satchel Charge's short hop."},{"when":"Late","text":"Late game you're a flanking assassin who can blink through his zone control and reset kills with Chronobreak, while Ziggs is purely a poke-and-siege mage who dies instantly if caught out of position, so hunt him in skirmishes and side lanes relentlessly."}],"wants":{"you":["Dodge his Bouncing Bomb poke early and punish predictable Satchel usage","Hop E onto him the instant he commits Satchel Charge to zone","Look for all-in windows near his jungle/turret where he can't kite"],"foe":["Poke safely from max range and farm with Bouncing Bomb bounces","Save Satchel Charge purely to zone and disengage your all-ins","Siege towers with W and R rather than contest lane skirmishes"]},"early":"From level 1 you already hold the edge because Ziggs has no mobility to punish your E-hop engages, and by levels 3-5 you can all-in the instant he uses Satchel Charge to zone since it's his only escape and now down for the whole wave, letting you snowball the lane hard if you play aggressively.","mid":"Levels 4-6 keep favoring you as your dash and stun let you close the distance on a champion who can only kite backward once, and your own level 6 Chronobreak lets you commit through his Mega Inferno Bomb zone and still walk away alive, making his ultimate a much weaker all-in tool than yours in a lane skirmish.","late":"With items you simply delete him in one rotation before he can kite away, and Chronobreak resets punish any panic Satchel Charge hop, so you should be actively hunting him in side lanes and skirmishes rather than just farming, since Ziggs offers almost nothing defensively once you're on top of him.","whys":["Ekko already wins level 1 trades since Ziggs has no mobility to punish your dash-based engages.","Level 2 continues to favor Ekko as his hop-and-stun combo outclasses Ziggs' immobile poke kit.","Levels 3-5 favor Ekko because he can punish Ziggs' Satchel Charge usage with a free all-in window.","The mid-game power spike still favors Ekko as his engage range keeps outclassing Ziggs' kiting options.","Ekko's level 6 Chronobreak lets him dive through Ziggs' zone control and win the skirmish outright.","Ekko continues to dominate skirmishes since his dash negates Ziggs' single defensive tool.","Ekko's item power and reset potential make him a dominant late-game threat against an immobile mage."]},
  {"a":"ekko_mid","b":"zoe","win":["Ekko","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko","Ekko"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Zoe's Sleepy Trouble Bubble threat is real but she has no mobility beyond Portal Jump onto a thrown item, so once you commit E onto her at level 3+ she can't escape your follow-up Q-AA-W, and punishing her for chunking wave with Spell Thief is a free trade."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Your Chronobreak lets you dive her the instant she uses Portal Jump to escape, since the reset window catches her before she can disengage further, while her own ult is just a slow, low-impact laser with no repositioning value for her personally."},{"when":"1st item","text":"With a first item you burst her down before her bubble sleep-into-Q combo lands twice, and any all-in near mid-lane bushes near your jungle is close to guaranteed since she has zero escape once Portal Jump is spent."},{"when":"Late","text":"Late game you're the flank-and-reset assassin while Zoe is a pure poke-and-pick mage who folds instantly if caught, so use Chronobreak to punish her positioning in skirmishes and pressure her off safe casting range whenever she's near your jungle."}],"wants":{"you":["Dodge her Bubble sleep setups and punish when Spell Thief is down","Hop E onto her once she's spent Portal Jump to escape","Force all-ins in bushes/jungle where she can't kite backward"],"foe":["Poke from max range with Q and land Bubble sleep for burst combos","Save Portal Jump purely as an escape, not an engage tool","Farm safely under tower and avoid extended lane skirmishes"]},"early":"You already hold the edge from level 1 since Zoe's only real mobility is a reactive Portal Jump onto a thrown item, meaning your E-hop engages are hard to answer, and by levels 3-5 punishing her for using Spell Thief or Portal Jump to disengage nets you a clean all-in almost every time.","mid":"The mid-game keeps favoring you as your dash lets you close distance on a champion who can only escape once per engage, and your own level 6 Chronobreak turns any of her Portal Jump disengages into a free dive-and-reset, while her ultimate offers no personal escape and barely threatens you in a skirmish.","late":"With items online you burst her down before her sleep-into-burst combo lands twice, and Chronobreak punishes any panic Portal Jump, so actively hunt her rather than farm passively, since Zoe has almost no defensive tools once you're in her face and her damage falls off relative to your scaling.","whys":["Ekko already wins level 1 trades since Zoe lacks reliable mobility to escape his dash-based engages.","Level 2 continues to favor Ekko as his hop-and-stun combo outpaces Zoe's setup-reliant poke kit.","Levels 3-5 favor Ekko because punishing Zoe's spent Portal Jump or Spell Thief nets a clean all-in.","The mid-game power spike still favors Ekko as his engage range keeps outclassing Zoe's single escape.","Ekko's level 6 Chronobreak lets him dive through Zoe's disengage and win the skirmish outright.","Ekko continues to dominate skirmishes since Zoe's ultimate offers no personal repositioning value.","Ekko's item power and reset potential make him a dominant late-game threat against a fragile poke mage."]}
